WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.968 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.968 --> 00:00:04.428 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.428 --> 00:00:06.396 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.396 --> 00:00:10.340 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.340 --> 00:00:14.255 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah, so, today, we
are going to start a new topic.

00:00:14.255 --> 00:00:30.790 align:middle line:90%


00:00:30.790 --> 00:00:32.290 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:00:32.290 --> 00:00:34.210 align:middle line:84%
So, first, we talk
about chiral fermions.

00:00:34.210 --> 00:00:41.560 align:middle line:90%


00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:53.050 align:middle line:84%
So remember, say, under
Lorentz transformation,

00:00:53.050 --> 00:01:04.840 align:middle line:84%
lambda, the Dirac spinor fields
transform as S lambda psi x.

00:01:04.840 --> 00:01:08.110 align:middle line:84%
And the x prime is a
Lorentz transformation of x.

00:01:08.110 --> 00:01:13.500 align:middle line:84%
So x prime is
lambda act on x, OK?

00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:16.060 align:middle line:90%


00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:31.790 align:middle line:84%
And then the S is given by, say,
omega mu nu, sigma, mu, nu, OK?

00:01:31.790 --> 00:01:35.300 align:middle line:84%
And the sigma mu, nu is driven
by the commutator of the gamma

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:37.100 align:middle line:90%
matrices.

00:01:37.100 --> 00:01:38.390 align:middle line:90%
So let me just write it down.

00:01:38.390 --> 00:01:40.400 align:middle line:90%
So sigma mu, nu--

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:43.400 align:middle line:84%
just remind you--
i divided by 4.

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:47.040 align:middle line:90%


00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:47.540 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:47.540 --> 00:01:53.030 align:middle line:90%


00:01:53.030 --> 00:01:56.610 align:middle line:90%
So one natural question--

00:01:56.610 --> 00:02:01.600 align:middle line:84%
so, previously, when we
derived the Dirac equation,

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:04.120 align:middle line:84%
we showed that the Dirac
equation requires, actually,

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:06.835 align:middle line:90%
psi to have four components, OK?

00:02:06.835 --> 00:02:11.990 align:middle line:90%


00:02:11.990 --> 00:02:14.570 align:middle line:84%
But, then, we showed that the
Dirac equation is covariant

00:02:14.570 --> 00:02:18.920 align:middle line:90%
if the psi transform this way.

00:02:18.920 --> 00:02:21.590 align:middle line:84%
So natural question is that
whether you can actually

00:02:21.590 --> 00:02:25.010 align:middle line:90%
restrict to a smaller part--

00:02:25.010 --> 00:02:27.690 align:middle line:90%
say, to a subset of psi--

00:02:27.690 --> 00:02:29.580 align:middle line:84%
whether they still have
well-defined Lorentz

00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:34.290 align:middle line:84%
transformation,
whether we actually

00:02:34.290 --> 00:02:37.980 align:middle line:84%
need to have four components
to have well-defined--

00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:40.440 align:middle line:84%
four complex component to
have well-defined Lorentz

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:42.660 align:middle line:90%
transformation, OK?

00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:46.470 align:middle line:84%
And the answer turns out
to be, no, you actually

00:02:46.470 --> 00:02:49.080 align:middle line:84%
don't need to have
four complex components

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:51.360 align:middle line:84%
to have well-defined
Lorentz transformation.

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:55.650 align:middle line:90%
Actually, you can reduce it, OK?

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:57.780 align:middle line:84%
And so there are two
ways to reduce it,

00:02:57.780 --> 00:02:59.610 align:middle line:84%
and one is called
chiral fermion,

00:02:59.610 --> 00:03:02.730 align:middle line:84%
and the one is called
the Majorana fermion, OK?

00:03:02.730 --> 00:03:06.830 align:middle line:84%
So one is called the
Majorana fermion.

00:03:06.830 --> 00:03:10.070 align:middle line:84%
So we first talk about the
chiral fermion and one way

00:03:10.070 --> 00:03:11.700 align:middle line:90%
to do it.

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:13.310 align:middle line:84%
So, for this
purpose, we will look

00:03:13.310 --> 00:03:17.120 align:middle line:84%
at the specific representation
of gamma matrices, OK?

00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:20.300 align:middle line:84%
Consider-- so now I will use
a representation which is

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:23.930 align:middle line:90%
different from what you--

00:03:23.930 --> 00:03:27.350 align:middle line:84%
so we consider
the following one.

00:03:27.350 --> 00:03:32.660 align:middle line:90%
Gamma 0 equal to 0, i, i, 0.

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:40.250 align:middle line:84%
Gamma i equal to 0 minus
i sigma i, i sigma i.

00:03:40.250 --> 00:03:45.010 align:middle line:90%


00:03:45.010 --> 00:03:48.360 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at this choice
of gamma matrices, OK?

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:55.500 align:middle line:84%
So I will call this
choice to be star, OK?

00:03:55.500 --> 00:03:58.410 align:middle line:90%
And so you can also work it out.

00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:01.450 align:middle line:90%
You find the sigma.

00:04:01.450 --> 00:04:05.340 align:middle line:90%
So sigma 0, i--

00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:08.560 align:middle line:84%
so this is the sigma
corresponding to the boost.

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:11.940 align:middle line:84%
So you find the sigma i, you
can just do the commutator.

00:04:11.940 --> 00:04:16.790 align:middle line:84%
From the sigma i is equal
to minus i divided by 2,

00:04:16.790 --> 00:04:19.170 align:middle line:90%
have this block diagonal form.

00:04:19.170 --> 00:04:23.160 align:middle line:84%
Sigma i 0, 0 sigma i--
again, the small sigma i

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:26.130 align:middle line:90%
is always the Pauli matrices.

00:04:26.130 --> 00:04:30.930 align:middle line:84%
And then you can also
work out the sigma ij.

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:35.040 align:middle line:84%
Then you find the is
given by minus 1/2,

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:46.590 align:middle line:84%
epsilon ijk, then sigma
k, 0, 0, sigma k, OK?

00:04:46.590 --> 00:04:47.110 align:middle line:90%
Oh, sorry.

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:50.140 align:middle line:90%
Here, there's a minus sign.

00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:53.190 align:middle line:90%
OK, here, there's a minus sign.

00:04:53.190 --> 00:04:59.890 align:middle line:84%
OK, so you find that they
have the following form.

00:04:59.890 --> 00:05:01.620 align:middle line:84%
So what do you
observe about this?

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:05.320 align:middle line:90%


00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:08.570 align:middle line:90%
So do you see something?

00:05:08.570 --> 00:05:09.100 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:10.475 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: They're
block diagonal.

00:05:10.475 --> 00:05:12.290 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yes, they
are block diagonal.

00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:15.100 align:middle line:84%
So if sigma is block
diagonal, then that

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:20.640 align:middle line:84%
means this S is also
block diagonal, OK?

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:23.370 align:middle line:84%
So when S is block diagonal,
what does that mean?

00:05:23.370 --> 00:05:30.350 align:middle line:90%


00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:31.557 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:05:31.557 --> 00:05:33.409 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:33.409 --> 00:05:33.992 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Hmm?

00:05:33.992 --> 00:05:34.970 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:36.790 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Exactly.

00:05:36.790 --> 00:05:41.740 align:middle line:84%
So when the S is block diagonal,
that means, when I write psi--

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:43.750 align:middle line:90%
so, psi-- have four components.

00:05:43.750 --> 00:05:46.720 align:middle line:84%
That means that the upper two
component and the lower two

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:49.940 align:middle line:84%
components-- they don't
transform to each other, OK?

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:51.590 align:middle line:84%
They only transform
within themselves.

00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:54.080 align:middle line:84%
They don't transform
to each other, OK?

00:05:54.080 --> 00:06:02.135 align:middle line:84%
So if I choose, that means
this lambda is block diagonal.

00:06:02.135 --> 00:06:06.290 align:middle line:90%


00:06:06.290 --> 00:06:16.751 align:middle line:84%
So that means, if I write psi x
into two component vector, psi

00:06:16.751 --> 00:06:21.560 align:middle line:84%
L and psi R, so I denote the
upper two components by psi L

00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:24.956 align:middle line:84%
and lower two
components by psi R--

00:06:24.956 --> 00:06:31.900 align:middle line:84%
are two component
complex vector.

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:37.980 align:middle line:90%


00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:47.010 align:middle line:84%
That means, under Lorentz
transformation, under S lambda,

00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:50.760 align:middle line:90%
psi L and psi R do not mix.

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:54.690 align:middle line:90%


00:06:54.690 --> 00:06:58.540 align:middle line:84%
So they just transform
among themselves.

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:00.190 align:middle line:84%
They just transform
among themselves.

00:07:00.190 --> 00:07:02.460 align:middle line:84%
So they actually have
well-defined Lorentz

00:07:02.460 --> 00:07:05.610 align:middle line:84%
transformation as
a smaller unit, OK?

00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:07.860 align:middle line:84%
You don't need four components
to be able to transform

00:07:07.860 --> 00:07:09.068 align:middle line:90%
under Lorentz transformation.

00:07:09.068 --> 00:07:10.480 align:middle line:84%
Actually, at least
two components

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:13.380 align:middle line:90%
can already transform.

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:15.410 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:15.410 --> 00:07:32.500 align:middle line:84%
So this tells you, in a sense
that the Lorentz covariance

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:39.850 align:middle line:84%
only requires two
component spinors.

00:07:39.850 --> 00:07:43.690 align:middle line:90%


00:07:43.690 --> 00:07:45.580 align:middle line:84%
Just by Lorentz
transformation itself,

00:07:45.580 --> 00:07:47.410 align:middle line:84%
you don't actually
need four components.

00:07:47.410 --> 00:07:50.390 align:middle line:90%


00:07:50.390 --> 00:07:50.890 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:50.890 --> 00:07:54.108 align:middle line:90%


00:07:54.108 --> 00:07:55.900 align:middle line:84%
So, now, I'm going to
tell you, we actually

00:07:55.900 --> 00:07:59.000 align:middle line:90%
knew this all along.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:04.060 align:middle line:84%
So how did we know
this all along?

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:04.690 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:08:04.690 --> 00:08:07.030 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why is
there no [INAUDIBLE]??

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:15.883 align:middle line:90%


00:08:15.883 --> 00:08:16.550 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Sorry.

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:17.745 align:middle line:90%
Say it again.

00:08:17.745 --> 00:08:21.511 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Didn't we have to
go to four components in there

00:08:21.511 --> 00:08:26.435 align:middle line:84%
because there are no
representation [INAUDIBLE]??

00:08:26.435 --> 00:08:27.310 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah.

00:08:27.310 --> 00:08:30.760 align:middle line:84%
We have to go to four
components because there's

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:36.730 align:middle line:84%
no two component representation
of the gamma matrices.

00:08:36.730 --> 00:08:39.610 align:middle line:84%
But that doesn't say it's
a Lorentz transformation.

00:08:39.610 --> 00:08:40.299 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:08:40.299 --> 00:08:43.330 align:middle line:84%
To write down the algebra
for the gamma matrices,

00:08:43.330 --> 00:08:46.040 align:middle line:90%
you need four components.

00:08:46.040 --> 00:08:50.060 align:middle line:84%
But we actually knew all
along that two components

00:08:50.060 --> 00:08:54.340 align:middle line:84%
is enough for Lorentz
transformation.

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:57.440 align:middle line:84%
How do we actually
know all along?

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:00.495 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Lorentz assumption
isn't just [INAUDIBLE] spin

00:09:00.495 --> 00:09:03.710 align:middle line:84%
like difference between
the [INAUDIBLE]??

00:09:03.710 --> 00:09:06.380 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah, this is
maybe more complicated.

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:08.240 align:middle line:90%
We have something much simpler.

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:09.407 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:09:09.407 --> 00:09:10.990 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is it the
massless particle?

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:12.460 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, exactly.

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:17.020 align:middle line:84%
So we already said before, if
you have a massless case when

00:09:17.020 --> 00:09:19.870 align:middle line:84%
m equal to 0, and
the Dirac equation

00:09:19.870 --> 00:09:23.790 align:middle line:84%
reduces to the two
components, and it's

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:26.460 align:middle line:84%
enough to do two components,
and the Dirac equation

00:09:26.460 --> 00:09:27.810 align:middle line:90%
is covariant, OK?

00:09:27.810 --> 00:09:29.460 align:middle line:84%
And so that means
that, actually, you

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:31.920 align:middle line:84%
should be able to do it
with two components, OK?

00:09:31.920 --> 00:09:33.503 align:middle line:84%
Because the massless
particle-- they

00:09:33.503 --> 00:09:35.920 align:middle line:84%
should be able to transform
on the Lorentz transformation.

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:37.530 align:middle line:90%
And so, yeah.

00:09:37.530 --> 00:09:44.660 align:middle line:90%


00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:49.100 align:middle line:84%
So we already saw this
because the massless.

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:57.590 align:middle line:84%
So the hint from before
is that the massless only

00:09:57.590 --> 00:10:06.470 align:middle line:90%
require two components.

00:10:06.470 --> 00:10:09.690 align:middle line:90%


00:10:09.690 --> 00:10:11.390 align:middle line:84%
Since the massless
case must also be

00:10:11.390 --> 00:10:13.295 align:middle line:90%
Lorentz covariant so that--

00:10:13.295 --> 00:10:14.930 align:middle line:84%
and Lorentz symmetry
itself should only

00:10:14.930 --> 00:10:16.830 align:middle line:90%
require two components.

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:20.660 align:middle line:84%
So it is not a Lorentz
symmetry, actually.

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:23.300 align:middle line:84%
Lorentz covariance
requires Dirac theory

00:10:23.300 --> 00:10:24.440 align:middle line:90%
to have four component.

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:26.990 align:middle line:90%
It is the mass, OK?

00:10:26.990 --> 00:10:28.310 align:middle line:90%
So it is the mass--

00:10:28.310 --> 00:10:33.620 align:middle line:90%


00:10:33.620 --> 00:10:35.090 align:middle line:90%
mass m.

00:10:35.090 --> 00:10:39.170 align:middle line:84%
If you want to describe
a massive particle,

00:10:39.170 --> 00:10:42.170 align:middle line:84%
then you must have
four components, OK?

00:10:42.170 --> 00:10:44.690 align:middle line:84%
So it is the mass
which is the key.

00:10:44.690 --> 00:11:03.650 align:middle line:90%


00:11:03.650 --> 00:11:04.710 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:11:04.710 --> 00:11:05.735 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:11:05.735 --> 00:11:13.220 align:middle line:90%


00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:18.590 align:middle line:84%
So, now, we have shown in
this particular representation

00:11:18.590 --> 00:11:20.780 align:middle line:84%
of gamma matrices, for
this particular choice

00:11:20.780 --> 00:11:28.330 align:middle line:84%
of gamma matrices, and then the
psi transform block diagonally.

00:11:28.330 --> 00:11:34.110 align:middle line:84%
But then we also said, but,
now, consider a different choice

00:11:34.110 --> 00:11:36.450 align:middle line:90%
of gamma matrices.

00:11:36.450 --> 00:11:39.310 align:middle line:84%
And then this property
will not hold, OK?

00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:40.780 align:middle line:90%
This property will not hold.

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:43.960 align:middle line:84%
Now, the question
is that, does this--

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:47.440 align:middle line:84%
even with other gamma
matrices, can we actually

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:51.450 align:middle line:84%
reduce psi to some
smaller components?

00:11:51.450 --> 00:11:54.390 align:middle line:84%
The answer still
should still be yes

00:11:54.390 --> 00:11:58.410 align:middle line:84%
because we said that all
representation of gamma

00:11:58.410 --> 00:12:00.370 align:middle line:90%
matrices should be equivalent.

00:12:00.370 --> 00:12:03.960 align:middle line:84%
So if we can do it in this
choice of gamma matrices,

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:06.870 align:middle line:84%
then we should be able to
do it in any choice of gamma

00:12:06.870 --> 00:12:08.720 align:middle line:90%
matrices, OK?

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:12.580 align:middle line:84%
So, now, let me tell you how
to do it for the general gamma

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:13.080 align:middle line:90%
matrices.

00:12:13.080 --> 00:12:17.120 align:middle line:90%


00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:26.030 align:middle line:84%
So this property that you
can reduce to two components

00:12:26.030 --> 00:12:39.360 align:middle line:84%
should exist for all
choice of gamma matrices.

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:43.230 align:middle line:90%


00:12:43.230 --> 00:12:47.600 align:middle line:84%
Just for other choice
of gamma matrices,

00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:53.640 align:middle line:84%
to separate the psi into psi
L and psi R is more subtle.

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:56.670 align:middle line:84%
You no longer-- is just
simple the upper two component

00:12:56.670 --> 00:12:57.970 align:middle line:90%
or lower two component.

00:12:57.970 --> 00:13:02.040 align:middle line:84%
So we have to do a
little bit of work, OK?

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:05.610 align:middle line:84%
Actually, we don't need to
do much work if you actually

00:13:05.610 --> 00:13:09.630 align:middle line:90%
find the right trick, OK?

00:13:09.630 --> 00:13:12.960 align:middle line:84%
And so the beautiful
trick to do this

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:16.320 align:middle line:84%
for any choice of
gamma matrices is

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:18.195 align:middle line:84%
that you can introduce
the following object--

00:13:18.195 --> 00:13:23.610 align:middle line:90%


00:13:23.610 --> 00:13:24.855 align:middle line:90%
what is called gamma 5.

00:13:24.855 --> 00:13:28.840 align:middle line:90%


00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:35.170 align:middle line:84%
So gamma 5 is defined to be
i gamma 0, gamma 1, gamma

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:37.180 align:middle line:90%
2, gamma 3, OK?

00:13:37.180 --> 00:13:40.210 align:middle line:84%
So you take the product
of all the gamma

00:13:40.210 --> 00:13:46.860 align:middle line:84%
matrices together and then
with a factor of i, OK?

00:13:46.860 --> 00:13:50.490 align:middle line:84%
So the i there is for
the purpose that if you--

00:13:50.490 --> 00:13:52.980 align:middle line:90%
you can check yourself--

00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:56.760 align:middle line:84%
that the gamma 5 is
actually Hermitian.

00:13:56.760 --> 00:14:01.190 align:middle line:84%
So the i is there
for this purpose, OK?

00:14:01.190 --> 00:14:04.020 align:middle line:90%
You need i for this to be true.

00:14:04.020 --> 00:14:13.280 align:middle line:84%
You also can check yourself that
gamma 5 squared is equal to 1,

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:15.620 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:20.000 align:middle line:84%
So, this, you can almost
easily understand because it's

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.460 align:middle line:90%
all gamma 0, gamma 1, gamma 3.

00:14:22.460 --> 00:14:26.990 align:middle line:84%
So you multiply itself again
because any same gamma matrix,

00:14:26.990 --> 00:14:30.020 align:middle line:84%
they multiply
either 1 or minus 1.

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:32.360 align:middle line:84%
So you multiply them
together, in the end,

00:14:32.360 --> 00:14:33.950 align:middle line:90%
they can be either 1 or minus 1.

00:14:33.950 --> 00:14:37.370 align:middle line:84%
Just turns out, for this
choice of i, it's 1, OK?

00:14:37.370 --> 00:14:39.470 align:middle line:90%
So yeah.

00:14:39.470 --> 00:14:44.960 align:middle line:84%
And then you can also check
the gamma 5 anticommute

00:14:44.960 --> 00:14:46.115 align:middle line:90%
with any gamma matrices.

00:14:46.115 --> 00:14:49.070 align:middle line:90%


00:14:49.070 --> 00:14:51.620 align:middle line:84%
So mu here is, of
course, from 0 to 3.

00:14:51.620 --> 00:14:54.550 align:middle line:90%


00:14:54.550 --> 00:14:59.120 align:middle line:90%
And so this is of--

00:14:59.120 --> 00:15:02.668 align:middle line:84%
you can see
immediately from here--

00:15:02.668 --> 00:15:03.960 align:middle line:90%
you can immediately from here--

00:15:03.960 --> 00:15:10.630 align:middle line:84%
because gamma matrices whose
indices are not the same,

00:15:10.630 --> 00:15:12.660 align:middle line:90%
they anticommute, OK?

00:15:12.660 --> 00:15:17.490 align:middle line:84%
So if you try to commute
this with any gamma matrices,

00:15:17.490 --> 00:15:18.870 align:middle line:90%
you have three of them.

00:15:18.870 --> 00:15:21.600 align:middle line:90%


00:15:21.600 --> 00:15:25.440 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, because this runs
over all gamma matrices.

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:29.810 align:middle line:84%
So the one in which-- yeah, so
if you take with some gamma mu,

00:15:29.810 --> 00:15:31.220 align:middle line:84%
and that particular
one, which is

00:15:31.220 --> 00:15:33.590 align:middle line:84%
the same as gamma mu, of
course, commutes with gamma mu.

00:15:33.590 --> 00:15:35.270 align:middle line:90%
But then you have three others.

00:15:35.270 --> 00:15:39.140 align:middle line:84%
But three others will
give you minus sign, OK?

00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:40.730 align:middle line:90%
And you can also check yourself.

00:15:40.730 --> 00:15:43.590 align:middle line:90%


00:15:43.590 --> 00:15:46.248 align:middle line:84%
Gamma 5 actually
have 0 trace, OK?

00:15:46.248 --> 00:15:47.790 align:middle line:84%
So, this, I will
leave as an exercise

00:15:47.790 --> 00:15:54.215 align:middle line:84%
for yourself, what you can do
is you did before with other--

00:15:54.215 --> 00:15:56.990 align:middle line:90%


00:15:56.990 --> 00:16:00.230 align:middle line:90%
yeah, in your homework--

00:16:00.230 --> 00:16:03.240 align:middle line:84%
yeah, similar to the exercise
you have done in your homework.

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:06.590 align:middle line:90%
So, now, from this properties--

00:16:06.590 --> 00:16:09.410 align:middle line:84%
now we can say the following
things about the gamma 5

00:16:09.410 --> 00:16:10.610 align:middle line:90%
matrix.

00:16:10.610 --> 00:16:17.900 align:middle line:84%
First, because gamma 5
squared, squared to 1.

00:16:17.900 --> 00:16:19.820 align:middle line:90%
And, also, this is Hermitian.

00:16:19.820 --> 00:16:25.300 align:middle line:84%
So it is Hermitian means its
eigenvalue is all real, OK?

00:16:25.300 --> 00:16:28.510 align:middle line:84%
So its eigenvalues are
all real, and gamma 5

00:16:28.510 --> 00:16:31.210 align:middle line:84%
squared equal to 1-- that
means its eigenvalue is either

00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:33.190 align:middle line:90%
plus or minus 1, OK?

00:16:33.190 --> 00:16:40.190 align:middle line:84%
So have eigenvalues
plus, minus 1.

00:16:40.190 --> 00:16:44.070 align:middle line:90%


00:16:44.070 --> 00:16:47.770 align:middle line:84%
And then from the property
that this is traceless,

00:16:47.770 --> 00:16:51.220 align:middle line:84%
they tell you the number of the
eigenvalues, which is plus 1,

00:16:51.220 --> 00:16:52.970 align:middle line:90%
and the number of minus 1.

00:16:52.970 --> 00:16:54.740 align:middle line:90%
They should be the same.

00:16:54.740 --> 00:16:56.110 align:middle line:90%
Otherwise, they won't cancel.

00:16:56.110 --> 00:16:57.370 align:middle line:90%
It won't be traceless.

00:16:57.370 --> 00:17:01.838 align:middle line:84%
And so each eigenspace
is two-dimensional.

00:17:01.838 --> 00:17:08.530 align:middle line:90%


00:17:08.530 --> 00:17:09.210 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:17:09.210 --> 00:17:12.160 align:middle line:90%
So you have four eigenvalues.

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:13.980 align:middle line:90%
So there's 2 plus 1, 2 minus 1.

00:17:13.980 --> 00:17:14.760 align:middle line:90%
It must be.

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:18.859 align:middle line:90%


00:17:18.859 --> 00:17:22.040 align:middle line:84%
So since you have eigenvalues
2 plus 1, 2 minus 1,

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:26.180 align:middle line:84%
and then we can introduce
a projector to project

00:17:26.180 --> 00:17:28.970 align:middle line:84%
into the eigenspace,
say, with plus 1--

00:17:28.970 --> 00:17:32.420 align:middle line:84%
with eigenvalue plus 1 or
the eigenvalue minus 1, OK?

00:17:32.420 --> 00:17:37.400 align:middle line:84%
So I can introduce a projector
which, for historical reasons,

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:39.760 align:middle line:90%
is called PL.

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:44.530 align:middle line:84%
It's defined to be
1/2 1 plus gamma 5.

00:17:44.530 --> 00:17:53.530 align:middle line:84%
And the PR is 1/2 1
minus gamma 5, OK?

00:17:53.530 --> 00:18:00.280 align:middle line:84%
So this will project into
eigenspace with the eigenvalue

00:18:00.280 --> 00:18:01.900 align:middle line:90%
plus 1 squared.

00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:06.200 align:middle line:84%
And this will project into an
eigenspace with a minus 1, OK?

00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:08.630 align:middle line:90%
Because when 1 minus 1 plus--

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:10.970 align:middle line:90%
yeah, anyway.

00:18:10.970 --> 00:18:12.530 align:middle line:90%
So you can check, OK?

00:18:12.530 --> 00:18:17.100 align:middle line:90%


00:18:17.100 --> 00:18:18.990 align:middle line:84%
So you can check they
are really projectors.

00:18:18.990 --> 00:18:24.060 align:middle line:84%
So PL squared equal to
PR squared equal to 1

00:18:24.060 --> 00:18:30.990 align:middle line:84%
and PLPR equal to 0 and PL
plus PR equal to identity, OK?

00:18:30.990 --> 00:18:34.460 align:middle line:90%


00:18:34.460 --> 00:18:39.220 align:middle line:90%
And then-- OK.

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:43.340 align:middle line:90%


00:18:43.340 --> 00:18:45.200 align:middle line:90%
So, now, I introduce--

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:51.020 align:middle line:90%


00:18:51.020 --> 00:18:53.810 align:middle line:90%
now I can project--

00:18:53.810 --> 00:18:59.510 align:middle line:84%
define the projection of psi L
of the projection of PL psi--

00:18:59.510 --> 00:19:03.500 align:middle line:90%
project to the left space, OK?

00:19:03.500 --> 00:19:06.950 align:middle line:84%
And psi R to be the
projection to the other space.

00:19:06.950 --> 00:19:10.770 align:middle line:90%


00:19:10.770 --> 00:19:11.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:11.270 --> 00:19:13.890 align:middle line:90%
I define them this way.

00:19:13.890 --> 00:19:17.360 align:middle line:84%
And then you can easily
see, by definition,

00:19:17.360 --> 00:19:20.870 align:middle line:84%
you can easily convince
yourself gamma 5 acting on psi

00:19:20.870 --> 00:19:23.990 align:middle line:84%
then just equal to psi
L. And the gamma 5 psi

00:19:23.990 --> 00:19:28.940 align:middle line:90%
R is equal to minus psi R, OK?

00:19:28.940 --> 00:19:32.240 align:middle line:84%
So they project into the
eigenvalues of plus, minus 1.

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:32.900 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:19:32.900 --> 00:19:33.890 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Wait,
why is PL squared

00:19:33.890 --> 00:19:35.170 align:middle line:90%
equal to PR squared plus 1?

00:19:35.170 --> 00:19:37.720 align:middle line:90%


00:19:37.720 --> 00:19:38.830 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Oh, sorry.

00:19:38.830 --> 00:19:40.700 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, sorry, sorry.

00:19:40.700 --> 00:19:41.530 align:middle line:90%
No, no.

00:19:41.530 --> 00:19:42.586 align:middle line:90%
This is good.

00:19:42.586 --> 00:19:45.250 align:middle line:90%


00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:47.200 align:middle line:90%
This is completely wrong, OK?

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:48.250 align:middle line:90%
This is completely wrong.

00:19:48.250 --> 00:19:50.350 align:middle line:90%
I was dreaming.

00:19:50.350 --> 00:19:56.450 align:middle line:84%
So PL squared equal
to PL, PR squared.

00:19:56.450 --> 00:19:57.020 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:19:57.020 --> 00:19:57.850 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, thank you.

00:19:57.850 --> 00:20:02.160 align:middle line:90%


00:20:02.160 --> 00:20:04.455 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so you can check
their projectors, OK?

00:20:04.455 --> 00:20:09.550 align:middle line:90%


00:20:09.550 --> 00:20:11.830 align:middle line:90%
So, indeed, you see--

00:20:11.830 --> 00:20:13.610 align:middle line:84%
so, from here, from
this definition,

00:20:13.610 --> 00:20:15.190 align:middle line:90%
you can check this is true, OK?

00:20:15.190 --> 00:20:17.530 align:middle line:90%
This is a one-second check.

00:20:17.530 --> 00:20:22.000 align:middle line:84%
And so, indeed, they project
to the eigenspace of gamma 5

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.910 align:middle line:90%
or plus, minus 1.

00:20:24.910 --> 00:20:26.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:26.790 --> 00:20:31.230 align:middle line:90%
So then, by definition--

00:20:31.230 --> 00:20:33.420 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now this
psi L, psi R, which

00:20:33.420 --> 00:20:37.180 align:middle line:84%
is now defined for any
choice of gamma matrices--

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:56.155 align:middle line:84%
so, again, they have to two
independent complex component,

00:20:56.155 --> 00:20:56.655 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:20:56.655 --> 00:21:08.270 align:middle line:90%


00:21:08.270 --> 00:21:14.440 align:middle line:84%
And so they call
the chiral spinors--

00:21:14.440 --> 00:21:17.590 align:middle line:90%


00:21:17.590 --> 00:21:19.480 align:middle line:84%
sometimes also
called Weyl spinors.

00:21:19.480 --> 00:21:23.830 align:middle line:90%


00:21:23.830 --> 00:21:27.910 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
analog of psi L and psi R

00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:32.790 align:middle line:84%
here for the general
choice of gamma matrices.

00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:36.820 align:middle line:84%
So, now, we will check
this actually, indeed.

00:21:36.820 --> 00:21:39.400 align:middle line:84%
So now the claim is
that psi L and psi R

00:21:39.400 --> 00:21:42.555 align:middle line:84%
defined this way will
transform under themselves

00:21:42.555 --> 00:21:43.930 align:middle line:84%
under the Lorentz
transformation.

00:21:43.930 --> 00:21:46.660 align:middle line:84%
They will not mix
with each other, OK?

00:21:46.660 --> 00:21:52.970 align:middle line:84%
So, again, psi L and psi R here
each have four components, OK?

00:21:52.970 --> 00:21:57.080 align:middle line:84%
They just have only two
independent compact components.

00:21:57.080 --> 00:21:59.860 align:middle line:84%
So they still have four
complex components, OK?

00:21:59.860 --> 00:22:02.020 align:middle line:84%
And there's still
four component spinors

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:06.850 align:middle line:84%
because just there's only
two independent ones.

00:22:06.850 --> 00:22:10.300 align:middle line:84%
There's only two
independent ones.

00:22:10.300 --> 00:22:15.250 align:middle line:84%
OK, so, now, it's easy to
check they actually transform

00:22:15.250 --> 00:22:16.790 align:middle line:90%
among themselves.

00:22:16.790 --> 00:22:27.820 align:middle line:84%
So you can check the
gamma 5 actually commutes

00:22:27.820 --> 00:22:29.355 align:middle line:90%
with sigma mu, nu.

00:22:29.355 --> 00:22:34.650 align:middle line:90%


00:22:34.650 --> 00:22:35.150 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:35.150 --> 00:22:39.660 align:middle line:90%


00:22:39.660 --> 00:22:41.475 align:middle line:90%
So this is very easy to see.

00:22:41.475 --> 00:22:44.470 align:middle line:90%


00:22:44.470 --> 00:22:48.510 align:middle line:84%
So, from here, gamma 5
commutes with any gamma

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:54.890 align:middle line:84%
mu or anticommute
with any gamma mu.

00:22:54.890 --> 00:22:57.920 align:middle line:84%
And the sigma mu, nu is
just the sum of two--

00:22:57.920 --> 00:23:00.260 align:middle line:90%
the product of two gamma mus--

00:23:00.260 --> 00:23:01.220 align:middle line:90%
have even gamma mus.

00:23:01.220 --> 00:23:06.460 align:middle line:84%
So the gamma 5 will
compete with them, OK?

00:23:06.460 --> 00:23:08.120 align:middle line:84%
So gamma 5 will
commute with them.

00:23:08.120 --> 00:23:10.210 align:middle line:84%
So if gamma 5 commutes
with sigma mu, nu,

00:23:10.210 --> 00:23:13.480 align:middle line:84%
then gamma 5 commutes
with S lambda

00:23:13.480 --> 00:23:18.530 align:middle line:84%
because S lambda just
generated by sigma mu, nu.

00:23:18.530 --> 00:23:19.535 align:middle line:90%
And then that means--

00:23:19.535 --> 00:23:22.060 align:middle line:90%


00:23:22.060 --> 00:23:24.360 align:middle line:84%
so we commute with
S. That means,

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:28.823 align:middle line:84%
under transformation,
S will not--

00:23:28.823 --> 00:23:30.240 align:middle line:84%
under transformation
by S will not

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:32.550 align:middle line:84%
change the eigenvalues
of gamma 5, OK?

00:23:32.550 --> 00:23:41.640 align:middle line:84%
So that means that psi L prime,
S lambda, psi L, and gamma

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:47.400 align:middle line:84%
5 acting on psi L
prime is still gamma L.

00:23:47.400 --> 00:23:48.900 align:middle line:84%
So it's still within
the same space.

00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:51.880 align:middle line:90%


00:23:51.880 --> 00:23:53.960 align:middle line:90%
And, similarly, we say--

00:23:53.960 --> 00:23:57.340 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that tells you
that psi L and psi

00:23:57.340 --> 00:24:00.910 align:middle line:84%
R-- they transform separately
because the gamma 5 commutes

00:24:00.910 --> 00:24:05.350 align:middle line:90%
with Lorentz transformation.

00:24:05.350 --> 00:24:07.830 align:middle line:84%
And so each eigenspace,
they transform separately

00:24:07.830 --> 00:24:09.520 align:middle line:90%
from each other.

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:10.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:10.020 --> 00:24:15.420 align:middle line:90%


00:24:15.420 --> 00:24:15.920 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:24:15.920 --> 00:24:16.837 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:24:16.837 --> 00:24:19.220 align:middle line:90%


00:24:19.220 --> 00:24:23.360 align:middle line:90%
So you can also find in the--

00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:34.180 align:middle line:84%
so in the chiral representation,
you can check in this star--

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:37.090 align:middle line:84%
so the star-- this
particular choice of gamma

00:24:37.090 --> 00:24:40.330 align:middle line:84%
is called the chiral
representation, OK?

00:24:40.330 --> 00:24:43.810 align:middle line:84%
Because in that
choice of gamma--

00:24:43.810 --> 00:24:46.060 align:middle line:84%
things simplify, we just
have upper two components

00:24:46.060 --> 00:24:47.570 align:middle line:90%
and lower two components.

00:24:47.570 --> 00:24:54.280 align:middle line:84%
So you can check yourself,
just by working it out,

00:24:54.280 --> 00:25:04.510 align:middle line:84%
that the gamma 5 indeed just
have block diagonal form--

00:25:04.510 --> 00:25:07.750 align:middle line:90%
1, 0, 0 minus 1, OK?

00:25:07.750 --> 00:25:08.830 align:middle line:90%
So that's why.

00:25:08.830 --> 00:25:11.320 align:middle line:84%
In that case, it's
very simple, OK?

00:25:11.320 --> 00:25:13.570 align:middle line:84%
But in other
representation, gamma 5

00:25:13.570 --> 00:25:14.680 align:middle line:90%
can be more complicated.

00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:23.120 align:middle line:90%


00:25:23.120 --> 00:25:23.620 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:25:23.620 --> 00:25:24.537 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:25:24.537 --> 00:25:31.760 align:middle line:90%


00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:34.100 align:middle line:90%
Yes, you have a question?

00:25:34.100 --> 00:25:35.480 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:35.480 --> 00:25:36.350 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:25:36.350 --> 00:25:38.267 align:middle line:84%
