00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:26.970 align:middle line:84%
OK, so let's go back to
this chiral representation

00:26:26.970 --> 00:26:30.270 align:middle line:84%
and write the
Dirac equation into

00:26:30.270 --> 00:26:32.027 align:middle line:90%
this chiral representation.

00:26:32.027 --> 00:26:36.950 align:middle line:90%


00:26:36.950 --> 00:26:38.705 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, one second.

00:26:38.705 --> 00:26:43.080 align:middle line:90%


00:26:43.080 --> 00:26:44.820 align:middle line:84%
So, now, if you write
the Dirac equation

00:26:44.820 --> 00:26:48.820 align:middle line:90%
in terms of psi L and psi R--

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:51.850 align:middle line:84%
so, remember, the Dirac
equation have the following form

00:26:51.850 --> 00:26:53.950 align:middle line:90%
of Dirac Lagrangian density.

00:26:53.950 --> 00:26:59.830 align:middle line:90%


00:26:59.830 --> 00:27:02.310 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:27:02.310 --> 00:27:06.720 align:middle line:84%
And then since psi is just
equal to the sum of the--

00:27:06.720 --> 00:27:14.820 align:middle line:90%
so psi-- psi R, OK?

00:27:14.820 --> 00:27:17.790 align:middle line:84%
And then you can just write
this in terms of psi L

00:27:17.790 --> 00:27:21.450 align:middle line:84%
and psi R. Write this in
terms psi L and psi R.

00:27:21.450 --> 00:27:24.150 align:middle line:84%
And then you find that
the cross term vanish.

00:27:24.150 --> 00:27:26.070 align:middle line:84%
You can also check
this explicitly

00:27:26.070 --> 00:27:29.130 align:middle line:84%
in the chiral representation,
but the expression

00:27:29.130 --> 00:27:31.230 align:middle line:90%
I'm writing down is general, OK?

00:27:31.230 --> 00:27:35.710 align:middle line:84%
So you can write
it as psi dagger

00:27:35.710 --> 00:27:48.945 align:middle line:84%
partial sub 0, plus i sigma i,
partial i, psi L. Yeah, sorry.

00:27:48.945 --> 00:27:53.470 align:middle line:90%


00:27:53.470 --> 00:27:55.210 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:27:55.210 --> 00:27:59.680 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, actually, psi R dagger.

00:27:59.680 --> 00:28:00.978 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let me first write.

00:28:00.978 --> 00:28:02.270 align:middle line:90%
I think I said something wrong.

00:28:02.270 --> 00:28:02.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, OK.

00:28:02.830 --> 00:28:40.850 align:middle line:90%


00:28:40.850 --> 00:28:41.350 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:28:41.350 --> 00:28:44.620 align:middle line:90%


00:28:44.620 --> 00:28:47.410 align:middle line:84%
So, yeah, as I said,
so this expression

00:28:47.410 --> 00:28:49.750 align:middle line:84%
only applies to the
chiral representation, OK?

00:28:49.750 --> 00:28:58.570 align:middle line:84%
So in the chiral
representation of gamma star--

00:28:58.570 --> 00:29:01.630 align:middle line:84%
in this space of star, and
then we have two components.

00:29:01.630 --> 00:29:04.090 align:middle line:84%
Then I can write this psi
and the psi L and psi R

00:29:04.090 --> 00:29:05.890 align:middle line:90%
into two components.

00:29:05.890 --> 00:29:07.720 align:middle line:90%
And then, yeah.

00:29:07.720 --> 00:29:10.390 align:middle line:84%
So this is just ordinary
sigma matrices, OK?

00:29:10.390 --> 00:29:14.470 align:middle line:90%


00:29:14.470 --> 00:29:17.140 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
expression you get, OK?

00:29:17.140 --> 00:29:20.170 align:middle line:90%


00:29:20.170 --> 00:29:21.265 align:middle line:90%
So what you notice--

00:29:21.265 --> 00:29:26.110 align:middle line:90%


00:29:26.110 --> 00:29:27.550 align:middle line:90%
is that for m equal to 0--

00:29:27.550 --> 00:29:30.760 align:middle line:90%


00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:44.620 align:middle line:84%
so there's no coupling
between psi L and psi R, OK?

00:29:44.620 --> 00:29:48.700 align:middle line:84%
So it's the mass term which
coupled them together, OK?

00:29:48.700 --> 00:29:50.860 align:middle line:90%
Kinetic term-- psi L--

00:29:50.860 --> 00:29:56.380 align:middle line:84%
there's no cross term between
the psi L and psi R, OK?

00:29:56.380 --> 00:29:58.090 align:middle line:84%
And this behavior
is actually general.

00:29:58.090 --> 00:30:00.277 align:middle line:84%
You can write it in
arbitrary representations.

00:30:00.277 --> 00:30:02.110 align:middle line:84%
But, of course, in
arbitrary representation,

00:30:02.110 --> 00:30:04.510 align:middle line:84%
I can no longer use
this sigma i, OK?

00:30:04.510 --> 00:30:10.630 align:middle line:90%
And so in this particular form--

00:30:10.630 --> 00:30:12.610 align:middle line:84%
even though this
feature is general,

00:30:12.610 --> 00:30:15.340 align:middle line:84%
but this particular
form of the kinetic term

00:30:15.340 --> 00:30:18.630 align:middle line:84%
only applies for the
chiral representation.

00:30:18.630 --> 00:30:19.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:19.130 --> 00:30:22.460 align:middle line:90%


00:30:22.460 --> 00:30:26.660 align:middle line:84%
So for m equal to 0, you don't
have coupling between the psi L

00:30:26.660 --> 00:30:31.360 align:middle line:84%
and psi R. And then you only
have to say, oh, diagonal

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:33.560 align:middle line:90%
term and psi R term.

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:38.320 align:middle line:84%
And then that gives
you something else, OK?

00:30:38.320 --> 00:30:41.200 align:middle line:84%
So, again, this is reduced
to our previous statement

00:30:41.200 --> 00:30:43.420 align:middle line:84%
that if you have
a massless case,

00:30:43.420 --> 00:30:46.000 align:middle line:84%
you can describe using a
two-component spinor, OK?

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.160 align:middle line:90%
So here, indeed.

00:30:48.160 --> 00:30:51.290 align:middle line:84%
But, here, there's
also something extra.

00:30:51.290 --> 00:30:52.420 align:middle line:90%
So what do you see--

00:30:52.420 --> 00:30:53.590 align:middle line:90%
something extra here?

00:30:53.590 --> 00:30:59.970 align:middle line:90%


00:30:59.970 --> 00:31:01.110 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:01.110 --> 00:31:03.210 align:middle line:90%
Did somebody raise your-- yes.

00:31:03.210 --> 00:31:05.080 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:31:05.080 --> 00:31:06.104 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:31:06.104 --> 00:31:10.944 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why are we now taking
the psi equals psi L plus psi

00:31:10.944 --> 00:31:15.532 align:middle line:84%
R instead of before we
had it as psi L and Psi R

00:31:15.532 --> 00:31:16.490 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Right, right.

00:31:16.490 --> 00:31:17.120 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

00:31:17.120 --> 00:31:18.850 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:31:18.850 --> 00:31:19.998 align:middle line:90%
A good question.

00:31:19.998 --> 00:31:21.290 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, this expression is wrong.

00:31:21.290 --> 00:31:23.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:23.600 --> 00:31:25.810 align:middle line:90%
Somehow, I was doing a--

00:31:25.810 --> 00:31:27.330 align:middle line:90%
I was trying to-- yeah.

00:31:27.330 --> 00:31:30.210 align:middle line:90%


00:31:30.210 --> 00:31:32.490 align:middle line:84%
I remembered I wrote this
in the general basis,

00:31:32.490 --> 00:31:34.650 align:middle line:84%
but then I realized I only
wrote it in that basis.

00:31:34.650 --> 00:31:36.240 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, in the general
basis, I would

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:39.480 align:middle line:84%
have psi equal to psi
L plus psi R. Yeah.

00:31:39.480 --> 00:31:41.610 align:middle line:84%
But then I realized, I
only write the kinetic term

00:31:41.610 --> 00:31:43.590 align:middle line:90%
in this specific basis.

00:31:43.590 --> 00:31:46.410 align:middle line:90%


00:31:46.410 --> 00:31:46.910 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:31:46.910 --> 00:31:47.410 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:50.792 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so that expression does
not apply for the chiral basis

00:31:50.792 --> 00:31:51.875 align:middle line:90%
but apply for the general.

00:31:51.875 --> 00:31:56.710 align:middle line:90%


00:31:56.710 --> 00:32:00.590 align:middle line:84%
So here, actually,
something profound

00:32:00.590 --> 00:32:06.430 align:middle line:84%
happens because, when m equal to
0, when you don't have coupling

00:32:06.430 --> 00:32:09.490 align:middle line:84%
between psi L and
psi R, you actually

00:32:09.490 --> 00:32:11.980 align:middle line:90%
get the extra symmetry, OK?

00:32:11.980 --> 00:32:24.890 align:middle line:84%
So in the Dirac Lagrangian,
as we discussed earlier,

00:32:24.890 --> 00:32:28.150 align:middle line:90%
so we have a U1 symmetry.

00:32:28.150 --> 00:32:33.290 align:middle line:84%
Psi goes to exponential
i alpha psi, OK?

00:32:33.290 --> 00:32:35.810 align:middle line:84%
So this Dirac Lagrangian
is invariant under that

00:32:35.810 --> 00:32:37.070 align:middle line:90%
because the psi is complex.

00:32:37.070 --> 00:32:43.830 align:middle line:90%


00:32:43.830 --> 00:32:48.340 align:middle line:84%
But, now, psi L and psi
R-- they are separate.

00:32:48.340 --> 00:32:51.330 align:middle line:84%
So, now, I can actually
transform psi L and psi R

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:52.740 align:middle line:90%
separately, OK?

00:32:52.740 --> 00:32:57.030 align:middle line:84%
So under this transformation,
psi L and psi R

00:32:57.030 --> 00:32:59.760 align:middle line:90%
transform the same, OK?

00:32:59.760 --> 00:33:05.410 align:middle line:90%
But, now, m equal to 0--

00:33:05.410 --> 00:33:09.760 align:middle line:84%
I can have psi L goes to
exponential i alpha L,

00:33:09.760 --> 00:33:22.710 align:middle line:84%
psi L. Psi R goes to exponential
i alpha R, psi R because they

00:33:22.710 --> 00:33:26.640 align:middle line:90%
only couple to themselves, OK?

00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:32.390 align:middle line:84%
And, now, I have
this symmetry, OK?

00:33:32.390 --> 00:33:36.770 align:middle line:84%
And so, now-- so,
here, you have U1,

00:33:36.770 --> 00:33:43.340 align:middle line:84%
and now you have U1 times U1
called U1 times L and U1R.

00:33:43.340 --> 00:33:48.430 align:middle line:84%
So these are called
chiral symmetries

00:33:48.430 --> 00:33:52.240 align:middle line:84%
because they transform the
left and the right separately.

00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:55.335 align:middle line:90%


00:33:55.335 --> 00:33:55.835 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:55.835 --> 00:34:01.090 align:middle line:90%


00:34:01.090 --> 00:34:01.750 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:34:01.750 --> 00:34:03.560 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I'm a
little bit confused

00:34:03.560 --> 00:34:06.430 align:middle line:84%
why you can't write psi as the
sum of the two projections?

00:34:06.430 --> 00:34:07.120 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Sorry?

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:08.643 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why you
can't write psi

00:34:08.643 --> 00:34:10.060 align:middle line:84%
as the sum of the
two projections?

00:34:10.060 --> 00:34:10.601 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No.

00:34:10.601 --> 00:34:12.810 align:middle line:84%
No, I can write it-- no,
I can write it that way.

00:34:12.810 --> 00:34:16.710 align:middle line:84%
Just, now, I'm using
the two-component form.

00:34:16.710 --> 00:34:19.739 align:middle line:84%
When I write two-component
form, then I write psi that way,

00:34:19.739 --> 00:34:24.960 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't make sense because
psi L is the upper two

00:34:24.960 --> 00:34:27.030 align:middle line:84%
component, and psi R is
the lower two component.

00:34:27.030 --> 00:34:27.800 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:34:27.800 --> 00:34:28.800 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

00:34:28.800 --> 00:34:32.550 align:middle line:84%
I'm using the same
notation for this spaces.

00:34:32.550 --> 00:34:35.310 align:middle line:84%
And so in these spaces,
psi L and psi R,

00:34:35.310 --> 00:34:36.630 align:middle line:90%
they only have two components.

00:34:36.630 --> 00:34:39.780 align:middle line:84%
But in the general case, there
have four components, OK?

00:34:39.780 --> 00:34:42.429 align:middle line:84%
So in the general case, I
can write psi equal to psi L

00:34:42.429 --> 00:34:45.190 align:middle line:84%
and psi R. But in
these spaces, I cannot.

00:34:45.190 --> 00:34:47.651 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, using this
notation, I cannot.

00:34:47.651 --> 00:34:55.719 align:middle line:90%


00:34:55.719 --> 00:35:00.160 align:middle line:84%
So, now, you have a
new symmetry equal to--

00:35:00.160 --> 00:35:09.410 align:middle line:84%
which you can transform
them separately, OK?

00:35:09.410 --> 00:35:12.110 align:middle line:84%
And the symmetries are one
of the most important aspect

00:35:12.110 --> 00:35:15.930 align:middle line:84%
of physics, and they have
very important implications,

00:35:15.930 --> 00:35:16.920 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:35:16.920 --> 00:35:23.990 align:middle line:84%
And the chiral symmetry actually
has also very important effect

00:35:23.990 --> 00:35:26.780 align:middle line:90%
in particle physics--

00:35:26.780 --> 00:35:30.020 align:middle line:90%
for example, the pions.

00:35:30.020 --> 00:35:33.290 align:middle line:90%
The pions has to do with--

00:35:33.290 --> 00:35:35.180 align:middle line:90%
I will not go into detail.

00:35:35.180 --> 00:35:39.890 align:middle line:84%
The pions-- they essentially
come from the chiral

00:35:39.890 --> 00:35:41.360 align:middle line:90%
symmetries.

00:35:41.360 --> 00:35:43.700 align:middle line:84%
Without the chiral
symmetries, there's no pion.

00:35:43.700 --> 00:35:46.070 align:middle line:90%
There's no pions, OK?

00:35:46.070 --> 00:35:51.620 align:middle line:84%
And actually understanding
how the pions

00:35:51.620 --> 00:35:53.920 align:middle line:84%
come from the chiral
symmetries, et cetera--

00:35:53.920 --> 00:35:58.110 align:middle line:84%
there was a Nobel Prize to
Nambu a number of years ago,

00:35:58.110 --> 00:35:59.930 align:middle line:84%
which our colleague
Goldstone also

00:35:59.930 --> 00:36:04.560 align:middle line:84%
made a very important
contribution to that.

00:36:04.560 --> 00:36:08.750 align:middle line:84%
And, also, nature--
also interesting

00:36:08.750 --> 00:36:12.540 align:middle line:84%
about this chiral symmetry
is that they are there.

00:36:12.540 --> 00:36:14.990 align:middle line:84%
Say, if you have a
classical massless-- say,

00:36:14.990 --> 00:36:18.920 align:middle line:84%
if you have a
massless Lagrangian,

00:36:18.920 --> 00:36:21.890 align:middle line:84%
then you can have the symmetry
in the classical level,

00:36:21.890 --> 00:36:23.430 align:middle line:90%
in the Lagrangian level.

00:36:23.430 --> 00:36:24.980 align:middle line:84%
But once you
quantize this theory,

00:36:24.980 --> 00:36:28.140 align:middle line:90%
you find the symmetry goes away.

00:36:28.140 --> 00:36:29.130 align:middle line:90%
It becomes anomalous.

00:36:29.130 --> 00:36:30.840 align:middle line:90%
It could become anomalous.

00:36:30.840 --> 00:36:33.090 align:middle line:84%
Symmetry is only present
in the classical level

00:36:33.090 --> 00:36:36.777 align:middle line:90%
but not in the quantum level.

00:36:36.777 --> 00:36:38.610 align:middle line:84%
And, again, that plays
a very important role

00:36:38.610 --> 00:36:40.130 align:middle line:90%
in particle physics, actually.

00:36:40.130 --> 00:36:40.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:40.630 --> 00:36:44.280 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, the bottom line is
that the chiral symmetry

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:49.470 align:middle line:84%
is very important in
many aspects of physics.

00:36:49.470 --> 00:36:52.200 align:middle line:84%
It's also important in many
condensed matter systems,

00:36:52.200 --> 00:36:54.880 align:middle line:90%
like liquid helium, et cetera.

00:36:54.880 --> 00:36:58.275 align:middle line:84%
So you can also write this
symmetry for general gamma.

00:36:58.275 --> 00:37:04.470 align:middle line:90%


00:37:04.470 --> 00:37:08.530 align:middle line:84%
So for general gamma, you can
have your previous symmetry.

00:37:08.530 --> 00:37:11.620 align:middle line:84%
So, now, I'm using the
four-component notation,

00:37:11.620 --> 00:37:15.490 align:middle line:84%
which psi L and psi R
transform the same way.

00:37:15.490 --> 00:37:17.205 align:middle line:84%
And then, now, you
have a new symmetry.

00:37:17.205 --> 00:37:22.280 align:middle line:90%


00:37:22.280 --> 00:37:25.760 align:middle line:90%
Gamma 5-- OK.

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:28.430 align:middle line:84%
And now you can put the
gamma 5 in the exponents.

00:37:28.430 --> 00:37:37.510 align:middle line:90%


00:37:37.510 --> 00:37:38.770 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:37:38.770 --> 00:37:40.230 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:37:40.230 --> 00:37:40.890 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:37:40.890 --> 00:37:42.365 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:42.365 --> 00:37:43.240 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah.

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:44.655 align:middle line:84%
Alpha tilde is just
some other constant--

00:37:44.655 --> 00:37:45.360 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Oh, alpha tilde.

00:37:45.360 --> 00:37:46.810 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: If tilde is
just some other constant,

00:37:46.810 --> 00:37:47.893 align:middle line:90%
then you multiply gamma 5.

00:37:47.893 --> 00:37:50.780 align:middle line:90%


00:37:50.780 --> 00:37:55.150 align:middle line:84%
So the way to understand
that these two are related--

00:37:55.150 --> 00:37:58.850 align:middle line:84%
so think about the
transformation here.

00:37:58.850 --> 00:38:02.330 align:middle line:84%
So, here, we can rewrite
a little bit differently.

00:38:02.330 --> 00:38:06.370 align:middle line:84%
We can consider rewrite
this alpha L and alpha R

00:38:06.370 --> 00:38:09.120 align:middle line:90%
in terms of the following.

00:38:09.120 --> 00:38:11.900 align:middle line:84%
Let's consider the two
transformation-- one

00:38:11.900 --> 00:38:16.350 align:middle line:84%
transformation, psi L, and
psi R transform the same.

00:38:16.350 --> 00:38:21.090 align:middle line:84%
And the other transformation is
that they transform oppositely.

00:38:21.090 --> 00:38:23.460 align:middle line:84%
They transform in the
opposite phase, OK?

00:38:23.460 --> 00:38:26.325 align:middle line:90%
So I write the alpha--

00:38:26.325 --> 00:38:28.350 align:middle line:84%
and this writing
is like that, OK?

00:38:28.350 --> 00:38:33.110 align:middle line:84%
So, in this way, psi L and psi
R transform the same, but--

00:38:33.110 --> 00:38:35.370 align:middle line:84%
psi L and psi R, they
transform opposite

00:38:35.370 --> 00:38:39.080 align:middle line:84%
because they have opposite
eigenvalue on the gamma 5.

00:38:39.080 --> 00:38:40.700 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
equivalent to that.

00:38:40.700 --> 00:38:46.660 align:middle line:90%


00:38:46.660 --> 00:38:47.210 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:49.870 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:38:49.870 --> 00:38:50.650 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:38:50.650 --> 00:38:54.500 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why is it called gamma
5 rather than, say, gamma 4?

00:38:54.500 --> 00:38:56.870 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: I think, again,
it's a historical reason.

00:38:56.870 --> 00:38:59.870 align:middle line:90%


00:38:59.870 --> 00:39:06.280 align:middle line:84%
So people often like to
go to Euclidean space.

00:39:06.280 --> 00:39:07.890 align:middle line:84%
So when you go to
Euclidean space,

00:39:07.890 --> 00:39:11.610 align:middle line:90%
you continue gamma 0 to gamma 4.

00:39:11.610 --> 00:39:14.310 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, just-- yeah, to gamma 4.

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:17.580 align:middle line:84%
And then you reserve
gamma 4 for that.

00:39:17.580 --> 00:39:19.530 align:middle line:84%
Then the gamma 5 is
the next one you take.

00:39:19.530 --> 00:39:22.133 align:middle line:90%


00:39:22.133 --> 00:39:22.800 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:39:22.800 --> 00:39:23.820 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:39:23.820 --> 00:39:27.030 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is there a
physical reason why

00:39:27.030 --> 00:39:29.190 align:middle line:90%
the massless case is special?

00:39:29.190 --> 00:39:31.050 align:middle line:84%
Is it because it
becomes scale-free,

00:39:31.050 --> 00:39:32.370 align:middle line:90%
or something like that?

00:39:32.370 --> 00:39:33.870 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah.

00:39:33.870 --> 00:39:36.510 align:middle line:84%
So massless case--
it's always special.

00:39:36.510 --> 00:39:39.810 align:middle line:84%
And you will see, in
physics, actually,

00:39:39.810 --> 00:39:43.260 align:middle line:84%
the massless case
actually gives you

00:39:43.260 --> 00:39:45.990 align:middle line:84%
very much richer
structure, normally,

00:39:45.990 --> 00:39:51.570 align:middle line:90%
than the massive particle.

00:39:51.570 --> 00:39:54.060 align:middle line:84%
Mathematically, it's
because the massless case--

00:39:54.060 --> 00:39:57.290 align:middle line:90%


00:39:57.290 --> 00:39:59.180 align:middle line:84%
in the massless case,
the representation

00:39:59.180 --> 00:40:01.490 align:middle line:84%
of the Lorentz group
is very different

00:40:01.490 --> 00:40:03.440 align:middle line:90%
from the massive case.

00:40:03.440 --> 00:40:05.390 align:middle line:84%
For example, if you
have a vector field,

00:40:05.390 --> 00:40:08.330 align:middle line:84%
say, for Maxwell
field, for the photon,

00:40:08.330 --> 00:40:10.910 align:middle line:84%
massless photon have
two polarizations.

00:40:10.910 --> 00:40:13.040 align:middle line:84%
But if you have a
massive vector--

00:40:13.040 --> 00:40:14.690 align:middle line:90%
say, for the photon is massive--

00:40:14.690 --> 00:40:16.850 align:middle line:84%
then we'll have
three polarizations.

00:40:16.850 --> 00:40:20.180 align:middle line:84%
And so the massless case
and the massive case

00:40:20.180 --> 00:40:22.400 align:middle line:90%
are very, very different.

00:40:22.400 --> 00:40:24.830 align:middle line:90%
The fermion case is the same.

00:40:24.830 --> 00:40:26.810 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
massive fermion,

00:40:26.810 --> 00:40:28.432 align:middle line:84%
you have four
complex components.

00:40:28.432 --> 00:40:30.140 align:middle line:84%
But if you have a
massless case, then you

00:40:30.140 --> 00:40:32.770 align:middle line:90%
have two complex components.

00:40:32.770 --> 00:40:34.270 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How about
very small mass?

00:40:34.270 --> 00:40:39.270 align:middle line:84%
Doesn't that cause a problem
if you go from x [INAUDIBLE]??

00:40:39.270 --> 00:40:40.242 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah.

00:40:40.242 --> 00:40:41.700 align:middle line:84%
That's a very
interesting question.

00:40:41.700 --> 00:40:43.075 align:middle line:84%
And there are a
lot of subtleties

00:40:43.075 --> 00:40:47.190 align:middle line:84%
associated with that kind
of questions, indeed.

00:40:47.190 --> 00:40:47.850 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:40:47.850 --> 00:40:49.516 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is there
any sense in which

00:40:49.516 --> 00:40:53.530 align:middle line:84%
we can treat psi L and psi R
as different dynamical fields,

00:40:53.530 --> 00:40:59.000 align:middle line:84%
like a complex scalar field
the case phi and phi star?

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:02.920 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Oh, psi L and psi
R certainly are independent--

00:41:02.920 --> 00:41:07.980 align:middle line:84%
you can certainly treat them
as independent dynamical, yeah.

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:08.940 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:41:08.940 --> 00:41:12.890 align:middle line:90%


00:41:12.890 --> 00:41:15.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:15.100 --> 00:41:19.690 align:middle line:84%
So let's conclude our discussion
of the chiral spinors.

00:41:19.690 --> 00:41:22.000 align:middle line:84%
And now we can talk about
the Majorana spinors.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:31.840 align:middle line:90%


00:41:31.840 --> 00:41:40.590 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the so the
Dirac spinor, which

00:41:40.590 --> 00:41:44.320 align:middle line:84%
we have talked about so
far, is four components.

00:41:44.320 --> 00:41:48.810 align:middle line:84%
So you have four times
two real components, OK?

00:41:48.810 --> 00:41:51.300 align:middle line:84%
And then the chiral
spinor we talked about--

00:41:51.300 --> 00:41:54.190 align:middle line:90%


00:41:54.190 --> 00:41:57.800 align:middle line:84%
essentially, you have
two complex components.

00:41:57.800 --> 00:42:02.150 align:middle line:84%
It's, say, 2 times 2
real components, OK?

00:42:02.150 --> 00:42:03.990 align:middle line:90%
2 times 2 real components.

00:42:03.990 --> 00:42:05.870 align:middle line:84%
So the next one I'm
going to talk about

00:42:05.870 --> 00:42:14.380 align:middle line:84%
is the Majorana, in which
case, I would argue,

00:42:14.380 --> 00:42:17.770 align:middle line:84%
we have 4 times
1 real component.

00:42:17.770 --> 00:42:21.920 align:middle line:84%
So it has four independent
real components, OK?

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:22.420 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:42:22.420 --> 00:42:24.600 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Sorry going
back real quick.

00:42:24.600 --> 00:42:27.630 align:middle line:84%
So I'm assuming R and L are for
right-handed and left-handed

00:42:27.630 --> 00:42:28.480 align:middle line:90%
in this [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:28.480 --> 00:42:30.990 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah,
yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:42:30.990 --> 00:42:34.960 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So can you ever
have a spinor where--

00:42:34.960 --> 00:42:37.780 align:middle line:84%
what does it mean to have
one of [INAUDIBLE] non-zero?

00:42:37.780 --> 00:42:40.140 align:middle line:84%
So both of them are
non-zero, I guess.

00:42:40.140 --> 00:42:41.910 align:middle line:84%
What is that--
because, in my mind,

00:42:41.910 --> 00:42:43.690 align:middle line:84%
it is either right-handed
or right handed.

00:42:43.690 --> 00:42:44.860 align:middle line:90%
What is the mixture of--

00:42:44.860 --> 00:42:46.090 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No, no, no, no.

00:42:46.090 --> 00:42:49.120 align:middle line:84%
Physically, electron
contains both left and right.

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:51.490 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so for massive
particle, because they always

00:42:51.490 --> 00:42:53.610 align:middle line:90%
couple together--

00:42:53.610 --> 00:42:56.930 align:middle line:84%
so the left hand, so psi
L turning into psi R,

00:42:56.930 --> 00:42:59.370 align:middle line:84%
psi R turning to
psi L all the time.

00:42:59.370 --> 00:43:03.430 align:middle line:84%
And for massive particle, you
cannot really separate them.

00:43:03.430 --> 00:43:09.520 align:middle line:84%
But, now, for massless particle,
then psi L and psi R-- yeah,

00:43:09.520 --> 00:43:12.710 align:middle line:84%
this is a very good question--
psi L and psi R are preserved.

00:43:12.710 --> 00:43:16.030 align:middle line:84%
So massless particle is
either psi L or psi R.

00:43:16.030 --> 00:43:20.140 align:middle line:84%
And then if you look at
their so-called helicity,

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:22.730 align:middle line:84%
it's either left-handed
or right-handed.

00:43:22.730 --> 00:43:26.620 align:middle line:84%
So that's where the name
psi L and psi R come from.

00:43:26.620 --> 00:43:29.180 align:middle line:84%
But, for the massive
particle, you cannot make this

00:43:29.180 --> 00:43:30.310 align:middle line:90%
separation.

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:32.440 align:middle line:84%
But for the massless
case, then it's preserved.

00:43:32.440 --> 00:43:37.820 align:middle line:84%
And then it's generally
left-handed or right-handed.

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:38.580 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:43:38.580 --> 00:43:41.450 align:middle line:84%
And, now, let's talk
about the last case--

00:43:41.450 --> 00:43:43.265 align:middle line:90%
this case, which is--

00:43:43.265 --> 00:43:45.645 align:middle line:84%
you have four real
components, OK?

00:43:45.645 --> 00:43:49.990 align:middle line:90%


00:43:49.990 --> 00:43:50.920 align:middle line:90%
So what do you do?

00:43:50.920 --> 00:43:53.440 align:middle line:84%
Again, we follow
the similar strategy

00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:58.780 align:middle line:84%
to see whether it's possible
to have four real components.

00:43:58.780 --> 00:44:01.900 align:middle line:84%
Again, we first-- the
idea is that you first

00:44:01.900 --> 00:44:05.230 align:middle line:84%
try to find the special
representation of gamma

00:44:05.230 --> 00:44:10.200 align:middle line:84%
matrices so that a spinor
that can be real, OK?

00:44:10.200 --> 00:44:13.260 align:middle line:84%
And then you try to generalize
to any representation of gamma

00:44:13.260 --> 00:44:14.470 align:middle line:90%
matrices.

00:44:14.470 --> 00:44:14.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:14.970 --> 00:44:18.100 align:middle line:90%


00:44:18.100 --> 00:44:26.050 align:middle line:84%
So, now, if you look
at the Dirac equation--

00:44:26.050 --> 00:44:47.392 align:middle line:90%


00:44:47.392 --> 00:44:48.725 align:middle line:90%
now, look at the Dirac equation.

00:44:48.725 --> 00:44:58.310 align:middle line:90%


00:44:58.310 --> 00:45:05.360 align:middle line:84%
So if I want to find
the real spinor,

00:45:05.360 --> 00:45:07.550 align:middle line:84%
then I ask myself
whether real spinor

00:45:07.550 --> 00:45:10.700 align:middle line:84%
is compatible with
this equation, OK?

00:45:10.700 --> 00:45:14.300 align:middle line:84%
So if the real scalar is not
compatible with this equation--

00:45:14.300 --> 00:45:17.300 align:middle line:84%
because I take the
complex conjugate,

00:45:17.300 --> 00:45:18.635 align:middle line:90%
I then take a gamma mu star.

00:45:18.635 --> 00:45:23.480 align:middle line:90%


00:45:23.480 --> 00:45:30.120 align:middle line:84%
If psi is real, then psi also
have to satisfy this equation,

00:45:30.120 --> 00:45:30.630 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:45:30.630 --> 00:45:34.400 align:middle line:84%
But, in general, gamma mu is
complex, as we wrote before--

00:45:34.400 --> 00:45:35.450 align:middle line:90%
yeah, I just erased it.

00:45:35.450 --> 00:45:39.270 align:middle line:84%
For example, in these
spaces, it's complex.

00:45:39.270 --> 00:45:42.670 align:middle line:84%
With complex, then these two
equations are not compatible,

00:45:42.670 --> 00:45:45.600 align:middle line:90%
and then psi cannot be real, OK?

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:46.290 align:middle line:90%
Simple as that.

00:45:46.290 --> 00:45:49.110 align:middle line:90%


00:45:49.110 --> 00:45:51.570 align:middle line:90%
But there's a way out.

00:45:51.570 --> 00:45:53.790 align:middle line:84%
The way out is
that, if they exist,

00:45:53.790 --> 00:45:58.690 align:middle line:84%
the representation of
gamma mu, the question

00:45:58.690 --> 00:46:06.720 align:middle line:84%
is whether there exists a
representation of gamma mu

00:46:06.720 --> 00:46:07.995 align:middle line:90%
so that gamma mu is real.

00:46:07.995 --> 00:46:13.680 align:middle line:90%


00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:18.570 align:middle line:84%
So if this is real, and then
these two equations become

00:46:18.570 --> 00:46:27.370 align:middle line:84%
the same, and then
for psi being real

00:46:27.370 --> 00:46:30.980 align:middle line:84%
is compatible with the
Dirac equation, OK?

00:46:30.980 --> 00:46:34.940 align:middle line:84%
It's compatible with
the Dirac equation.

00:46:34.940 --> 00:46:41.240 align:middle line:84%
So, now, let's-- so then this
becomes a question of trial

00:46:41.240 --> 00:46:42.710 align:middle line:90%
and error, OK?

00:46:42.710 --> 00:46:44.990 align:middle line:84%
So you try to find the
representation of gamma

00:46:44.990 --> 00:46:48.960 align:middle line:90%
matrices so that it's real OK.

00:46:48.960 --> 00:46:54.990 align:middle line:84%
And then it turns
out, you can find it,

00:46:54.990 --> 00:46:56.860 align:middle line:90%
and here is the answer.

00:46:56.860 --> 00:46:59.940 align:middle line:84%
So let me just write
down the answer.

00:46:59.940 --> 00:47:04.070 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how he
originally found it--

00:47:04.070 --> 00:47:07.895 align:middle line:84%
Majorana originally found
it, but here is the answer.

00:47:07.895 --> 00:47:32.290 align:middle line:90%


00:47:32.290 --> 00:47:35.600 align:middle line:90%
So this is four gamma matrices.

00:47:35.600 --> 00:47:37.900 align:middle line:84%
And you can see
there, each of them

00:47:37.900 --> 00:47:43.530 align:middle line:84%
is real because sigma 2 is pure
imaginary, and sigma 1, sigma 3

00:47:43.530 --> 00:47:44.920 align:middle line:90%
are real.

00:47:44.920 --> 00:47:46.630 align:middle line:90%
And so this is purely real.

00:47:46.630 --> 00:47:47.400 align:middle line:90%
And you can check.

00:47:47.400 --> 00:47:51.258 align:middle line:84%
This satisfied the algebra
of the government matrices.

00:47:51.258 --> 00:47:53.050 align:middle line:84%
They satisfy the algebra
of gamma matrices.

00:47:53.050 --> 00:47:57.990 align:middle line:84%
They anticommute with each
other, and each of them

00:47:57.990 --> 00:47:58.740 align:middle line:90%
square--

00:47:58.740 --> 00:48:00.653 align:middle line:90%
so each of them squaring 1.

00:48:00.653 --> 00:48:02.070 align:middle line:84%
So these three
square them into 1.

00:48:02.070 --> 00:48:03.300 align:middle line:90%
This square equal minus 1.

00:48:03.300 --> 00:48:12.480 align:middle line:90%


00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:15.210 align:middle line:84%
So, now, this is compatible
with Dirac equation,

00:48:15.210 --> 00:48:18.370 align:middle line:90%
but this is actually not enough.

00:48:18.370 --> 00:48:20.910 align:middle line:84%
We also have to be sure this
is compatible with the Lorentz

00:48:20.910 --> 00:48:24.430 align:middle line:90%
transformation, OK?

00:48:24.430 --> 00:48:26.930 align:middle line:84%
So, now, let's check whether
this is compatible with Lorentz

00:48:26.930 --> 00:48:29.130 align:middle line:90%
transformation.

00:48:29.130 --> 00:48:32.750 align:middle line:90%
So, now, we have this sigma mu--

00:48:32.750 --> 00:48:33.590 align:middle line:90%
gamma mu.

00:48:33.590 --> 00:48:36.800 align:middle line:84%
And, remember,
the sigma mu, nu--

00:48:36.800 --> 00:48:38.030 align:middle line:90%
I just erased it.

00:48:38.030 --> 00:48:43.290 align:middle line:90%


00:48:43.290 --> 00:48:47.810 align:middle line:84%
So now this is pure imaginary
because if gamma mu and gamma

00:48:47.810 --> 00:48:50.030 align:middle line:84%
nu are real, their
commutator is also real.

00:48:50.030 --> 00:48:53.750 align:middle line:84%
And then sigma mu, nu
will be pure imaginary.

00:48:53.750 --> 00:48:55.295 align:middle line:90%
And then that means S lambda--

00:48:55.295 --> 00:49:04.640 align:middle line:90%


00:49:04.640 --> 00:49:06.245 align:middle line:90%
so this is now purely real.

00:49:06.245 --> 00:49:10.260 align:middle line:90%


00:49:10.260 --> 00:49:12.610 align:middle line:90%
Now, this means this is real.

00:49:12.610 --> 00:49:14.800 align:middle line:90%
And, now, we are done, OK?

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:19.180 align:middle line:84%
That means that if we
take the psi is real, then

00:49:19.180 --> 00:49:24.010 align:middle line:84%
after Lorentz transformation,
this remains to be real, OK?

00:49:24.010 --> 00:49:27.550 align:middle line:84%
And so that means that it's
compatible with Lorentz

00:49:27.550 --> 00:49:29.260 align:middle line:90%
transformation.

00:49:29.260 --> 00:49:32.250 align:middle line:84%
So if we were not compatible
with Lorentz transmission,

00:49:32.250 --> 00:49:35.010 align:middle line:90%
then we were finished, OK?

00:49:35.010 --> 00:49:36.720 align:middle line:84%
So this shows that
this remains real.

00:49:36.720 --> 00:49:52.738 align:middle line:90%


00:49:52.738 --> 00:49:56.350 align:middle line:84%
So such a spinor is called
a Majorana spinor, OK?

00:49:56.350 --> 00:49:59.140 align:middle line:90%
So it has four real components.

00:49:59.140 --> 00:50:02.080 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, we wrote there-- it
has four real components.

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:06.940 align:middle line:90%


00:50:06.940 --> 00:50:11.230 align:middle line:84%
So you can quantize
it, which, I think

00:50:11.230 --> 00:50:14.140 align:middle line:84%
I will give it as an
exercise for you to do, OK?

00:50:14.140 --> 00:50:15.430 align:middle line:90%
You can quantize it.

00:50:15.430 --> 00:50:21.910 align:middle line:84%
And then, in this
case, then the fermions

00:50:21.910 --> 00:50:31.000 align:middle line:84%
are its own antiparticle, rather
than for the Dirac spinor.

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:32.950 align:middle line:84%
You have particle
and antiparticle,

00:50:32.950 --> 00:50:39.374 align:middle line:84%
so this is the analog of the
real scalar in the spinor case.

00:50:39.374 --> 00:50:42.100 align:middle line:90%


00:50:42.100 --> 00:50:48.490 align:middle line:84%
So this was discovered
by Majorana in 1937, OK?

00:50:48.490 --> 00:50:49.660 align:middle line:90%
And he was very young.

00:50:49.660 --> 00:50:52.240 align:middle line:90%
At the time, he was 31.

00:50:52.240 --> 00:50:57.670 align:middle line:84%
And, yeah, a brilliant
physicist, complete genius.

00:50:57.670 --> 00:51:01.070 align:middle line:90%
And then, in 1938--

00:51:01.070 --> 00:51:03.860 align:middle line:90%
so he lived in Sicily, OK?

00:51:03.860 --> 00:51:05.600 align:middle line:90%
So his hometown was in Sicily.

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:13.220 align:middle line:84%
So he boarded a ship
from Naples to Sicily.

00:51:13.220 --> 00:51:17.150 align:middle line:84%
And then he just disappeared
on the ship, never seen again.

00:51:17.150 --> 00:51:20.110 align:middle line:90%


00:51:20.110 --> 00:51:25.760 align:middle line:84%
At the age of 32,
he just disappeared.

00:51:25.760 --> 00:51:29.300 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, it's a quite--

00:51:29.300 --> 00:51:32.690 align:middle line:90%


00:51:32.690 --> 00:51:34.790 align:middle line:84%
yeah, extremely
brilliant physicist.

00:51:34.790 --> 00:51:35.900 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:51:35.900 --> 00:51:37.940 align:middle line:84%
And there are all
kinds of stories

00:51:37.940 --> 00:51:41.630 align:middle line:84%
about his disappearance--
that he may be killed by Mafia

00:51:41.630 --> 00:51:44.360 align:middle line:90%
or maybe suicide, et cetera.

00:51:44.360 --> 00:51:46.600 align:middle line:90%
But just nobody knows.

00:51:46.600 --> 00:51:47.925 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:51:47.925 --> 00:51:50.300 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: You said that all
the choices of gamma matrices

00:51:50.300 --> 00:51:51.260 align:middle line:90%
were equivalent.

00:51:51.260 --> 00:51:52.190 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:51:52.190 --> 00:51:54.410 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: This doesn't
really feel equivalent.

00:51:54.410 --> 00:51:56.650 align:middle line:84%
It is still equivalent to
the other representations?

00:51:56.650 --> 00:51:57.250 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah.

00:51:57.250 --> 00:51:58.270 align:middle line:90%
We will talk about that.

00:51:58.270 --> 00:52:02.070 align:middle line:90%


00:52:02.070 --> 00:52:07.940 align:middle line:84%
So now we have chosen a
very specific representation

00:52:07.940 --> 00:52:14.450 align:middle line:84%
for gamma matrices, which psi
can be chosen to be real, OK?

00:52:14.450 --> 00:52:21.170 align:middle line:84%
But how about for the
general representation?

00:52:21.170 --> 00:52:23.225 align:middle line:84%
So now we talk
about the general.

00:52:23.225 --> 00:52:29.240 align:middle line:90%


00:52:29.240 --> 00:52:34.360 align:middle line:90%
Majorana spinor-- yeah.

00:52:34.360 --> 00:52:36.060 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, also, let me
just make a remark.

00:52:36.060 --> 00:52:39.750 align:middle line:84%
Majorana spinor, of course,
also plays a very important role

00:52:39.750 --> 00:52:41.550 align:middle line:90%
in modern-day physics.

00:52:41.550 --> 00:52:45.720 align:middle line:90%


00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:51.810 align:middle line:84%
Say, for example, people suspect
a neutrino could be a Majorana

00:52:51.810 --> 00:52:53.310 align:middle line:90%
spinner, OK?

00:52:53.310 --> 00:52:57.330 align:middle line:84%
So to check whether a neutrino
is a Majorana spinor--

00:52:57.330 --> 00:53:00.600 align:middle line:90%


00:53:00.600 --> 00:53:03.990 align:middle line:84%
yeah, it's a forefront
experimental program--

00:53:03.990 --> 00:53:06.600 align:middle line:90%
has been pursued by many years.

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:12.990 align:middle line:84%
And, also, in condensed
matter, in quantum information,

00:53:12.990 --> 00:53:16.090 align:middle line:84%
and Majorana spinor play
a very important role.

00:53:16.090 --> 00:53:19.210 align:middle line:84%
And so, in condensed matter,
you only have electron.

00:53:19.210 --> 00:53:23.440 align:middle line:84%
So electron and the Majorana
spinor is, like, half electron,

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:23.940 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:53:23.940 --> 00:53:26.810 align:middle line:84%
Because the electron have
eight components, right?

00:53:26.810 --> 00:53:27.390 align:middle line:90%
Remember.

00:53:27.390 --> 00:53:29.170 align:middle line:84%
And Majorana only
have four components.

00:53:29.170 --> 00:53:32.190 align:middle line:84%
So Majorana is,
like, half electron.

00:53:32.190 --> 00:53:36.280 align:middle line:84%
So precisely because it's
heuristically half electron,

00:53:36.280 --> 00:53:40.210 align:middle line:84%
it has very stable
topological properties,

00:53:40.210 --> 00:53:43.150 align:middle line:84%
which a single
electron does not have.

00:53:43.150 --> 00:53:48.280 align:middle line:84%
And whether you can engineer in
your condensed matter systems,

00:53:48.280 --> 00:53:50.620 align:middle line:84%
Majorana spinor then
became a Holy Grail.

00:53:50.620 --> 00:53:54.220 align:middle line:84%
Because if you can do it,
and then you can do lots of--

00:53:54.220 --> 00:53:58.840 align:middle line:84%
yeah, you can achieve more
stable quantum computation,

00:53:58.840 --> 00:54:00.760 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:54:00.760 --> 00:54:01.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:54:01.510 --> 00:54:04.090 align:middle line:84%
During the last
number of years, there

00:54:04.090 --> 00:54:06.580 align:middle line:84%
have been various
experimental reports.

00:54:06.580 --> 00:54:10.480 align:middle line:84%
People say they have
engineered Majorana spinor

00:54:10.480 --> 00:54:14.920 align:middle line:84%
in the lab, which I think has
never been fully confirmed,

00:54:14.920 --> 00:54:15.880 align:middle line:90%
I think.

00:54:15.880 --> 00:54:18.130 align:middle line:84%
None of them has
been fully confirmed.

00:54:18.130 --> 00:54:23.310 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so, yeah, so, now,
let's talk about Majorana spinor

00:54:23.310 --> 00:54:33.415 align:middle line:84%
in general basis,
for general gamma mu.

00:54:33.415 --> 00:54:36.370 align:middle line:90%


00:54:36.370 --> 00:54:43.570 align:middle line:84%
So the idea would be similar to
the case of the chiral spinor.

00:54:43.570 --> 00:54:46.180 align:middle line:90%
For the chiral spinor--

00:54:46.180 --> 00:54:48.220 align:middle line:84%
in the chiral basis,
it's very simple, just

00:54:48.220 --> 00:54:51.780 align:middle line:90%
upper and lower components.

00:54:51.780 --> 00:54:54.020 align:middle line:84%
So, for the chiral
spinor, you have

00:54:54.020 --> 00:54:55.430 align:middle line:84%
to introduce some
other structure

00:54:55.430 --> 00:54:59.780 align:middle line:84%
to isolate psi L and
psi R. So you have to--

00:54:59.780 --> 00:55:02.000 align:middle line:84%
now, you have this
nontrivial condition, OK?

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:05.177 align:middle line:84%
And the chiral fermions come
from this nontrivial condition.

00:55:05.177 --> 00:55:09.280 align:middle line:90%


00:55:09.280 --> 00:55:10.900 align:middle line:84%
So, now, the key
is that, how do you

00:55:10.900 --> 00:55:16.070 align:middle line:84%
find the analogous condition
to the psi to be real

00:55:16.070 --> 00:55:18.560 align:middle line:90%
in the general basis, OK?

00:55:18.560 --> 00:55:23.370 align:middle line:84%
Because when gamma mu is
generally complex, clearly,

00:55:23.370 --> 00:55:25.730 align:middle line:84%
you cannot set the psi
equal to psi star, OK?

00:55:25.730 --> 00:55:27.290 align:middle line:90%
That does not make sense.

00:55:27.290 --> 00:55:30.530 align:middle line:84%
You have to find another
equivalent equation

00:55:30.530 --> 00:55:32.420 align:middle line:84%
to do, essentially,
the same thing, OK?

00:55:32.420 --> 00:55:35.180 align:middle line:90%
So that's the basic idea.

00:55:35.180 --> 00:55:41.430 align:middle line:84%
OK, so for this
purpose, we want to--

00:55:41.430 --> 00:55:43.950 align:middle line:84%
now, we use any
gamma matrices that

00:55:43.950 --> 00:55:47.090 align:middle line:84%
are equivalent to each other
up to a similar transformation,

00:55:47.090 --> 00:55:48.820 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:55:48.820 --> 00:55:59.840 align:middle line:84%
So let's denote-- this
basis by gamma m, OK?

00:55:59.840 --> 00:56:05.870 align:middle line:84%
And then we have gamma m, which
is this called Majorana basis.

00:56:05.870 --> 00:56:09.860 align:middle line:84%
And then any choice of gamma
mu then related to gamma m

00:56:09.860 --> 00:56:11.690 align:middle line:84%
by a similar
transformation-- that

00:56:11.690 --> 00:56:22.460 align:middle line:84%
means there exists some matrix
C that the C can take any gamma

00:56:22.460 --> 00:56:26.390 align:middle line:90%
mu into gamma mu m, OK?

00:56:26.390 --> 00:56:29.690 align:middle line:84%
So there must exist C, and
this equation is satisfied.

00:56:29.690 --> 00:56:37.265 align:middle line:90%


00:56:37.265 --> 00:56:37.765 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:56:37.765 --> 00:56:45.010 align:middle line:90%


00:56:45.010 --> 00:56:47.530 align:middle line:84%
So, now, given this
C, then we can easily

00:56:47.530 --> 00:56:59.260 align:middle line:84%
write down the condition
for the general basis

00:56:59.260 --> 00:57:09.190 align:middle line:84%
because under such
a change of basis,

00:57:09.190 --> 00:57:11.720 align:middle line:84%
the spinor in the Majorana
basis, which is real,

00:57:11.720 --> 00:57:14.900 align:middle line:84%
is related to the spinor
in the gamma mu basis

00:57:14.900 --> 00:57:18.840 align:middle line:90%
by this transformation C, OK?

00:57:18.840 --> 00:57:21.270 align:middle line:84%
So the C relates to
the gamma matrices.

00:57:21.270 --> 00:57:23.400 align:middle line:84%
But the C, of course, also
relates to the spinor.

00:57:23.400 --> 00:57:25.110 align:middle line:90%
It's just a change of basis, OK?

00:57:25.110 --> 00:57:29.840 align:middle line:84%
And so psi M will be
related to psi by C.

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:36.620 align:middle line:84%
And now, since the psi M
is equal to psi M star,

00:57:36.620 --> 00:57:43.920 align:middle line:84%
so that means that C star psi
star should be equal to C psi,

00:57:43.920 --> 00:57:44.420 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:57:44.420 --> 00:57:50.990 align:middle line:84%
So that means the psi star
should be equal to B psi

00:57:50.990 --> 00:57:59.390 align:middle line:84%
with B equal to C
minus 1 star C, OK?

00:57:59.390 --> 00:58:01.340 align:middle line:84%
So that should be the
condition which you

00:58:01.340 --> 00:58:02.705 align:middle line:90%
impose in the general basis.

00:58:02.705 --> 00:58:13.282 align:middle line:90%


00:58:13.282 --> 00:58:14.740 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that should
be the condition

00:58:14.740 --> 00:58:17.240 align:middle line:84%
you should impose in
the general basis.

00:58:17.240 --> 00:58:20.350 align:middle line:84%
So you have to introduce
this C. So if you find that

00:58:20.350 --> 00:58:28.410 align:middle line:84%
the transformation between the
general gamma mu and the gamma

00:58:28.410 --> 00:58:32.000 align:middle line:84%
mu m, and then you can
use that to find the B.

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:35.580 align:middle line:84%
And once you find the B, and
then you can find the-- you can

00:58:35.580 --> 00:58:36.540 align:middle line:90%
impose the--

00:58:36.540 --> 00:58:38.760 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so this is called
a Majorana condition

00:58:38.760 --> 00:58:39.840 align:middle line:90%
in the general basis.

00:58:39.840 --> 00:58:53.170 align:middle line:90%


00:58:53.170 --> 00:58:56.770 align:middle line:84%
So let's understand
a little bit.

00:58:56.770 --> 00:59:00.435 align:middle line:84%
So, actually, we can understand
the B more directly, OK?

00:59:00.435 --> 00:59:02.310 align:middle line:84%
So, here, we expanded
from C. But we actually

00:59:02.310 --> 00:59:05.220 align:middle line:90%
can find the B more directly.

00:59:05.220 --> 00:59:13.920 align:middle line:84%
We can just take the complex
conjugate of this equation

00:59:13.920 --> 00:59:16.830 align:middle line:90%
because gamma mu m is real.

00:59:16.830 --> 00:59:19.690 align:middle line:84%
So we can also take the complex
conjugate of this equation.

00:59:19.690 --> 00:59:28.997 align:middle line:84%
So that means that, since gamma
mu m equal to gamma mu m star,

00:59:28.997 --> 00:59:31.080 align:middle line:84%
but if we take complex
conjugate of that equation,

00:59:31.080 --> 00:59:35.370 align:middle line:84%
means that the C star
gamma mu, C minus 1 star

00:59:35.370 --> 00:59:40.770 align:middle line:84%
is equal to C gamma
mu, C minus 1.

00:59:40.770 --> 00:59:42.960 align:middle line:90%
And now, again, you just--

00:59:42.960 --> 00:59:43.815 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

00:59:43.815 --> 00:59:46.020 align:middle line:90%
This would be star, OK?

00:59:46.020 --> 00:59:48.750 align:middle line:84%
So, now, if we put all
the C to this side,

00:59:48.750 --> 00:59:56.280 align:middle line:84%
and then we find
gamma mu star is

00:59:56.280 --> 01:00:01.050 align:middle line:84%
just equal to B gamma
mu, B minus 1, OK?

01:00:01.050 --> 01:00:03.180 align:middle line:84%
So you just put
this to this side.

01:00:03.180 --> 01:00:05.280 align:middle line:84%
Then you just--
so this becomes B,

01:00:05.280 --> 01:00:09.300 align:middle line:84%
and then this becomes
B minus 1, OK?

01:00:09.300 --> 01:00:13.950 align:middle line:90%
So, now, we see that B--

01:00:13.950 --> 01:00:15.740 align:middle line:90%
this actually makes sense.

01:00:15.740 --> 01:00:20.530 align:middle line:84%
This is actually the matrix we
take gamma mu to gamma mu star,

01:00:20.530 --> 01:00:22.430 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:00:22.430 --> 01:00:25.735 align:middle line:84%
So B is the matrix
to take star, OK?

01:00:25.735 --> 01:00:31.830 align:middle line:90%


01:00:31.830 --> 01:00:32.330 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:00:32.330 --> 01:00:33.970 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

01:00:33.970 --> 01:00:35.432 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:00:35.432 --> 01:00:38.610 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
this is [INAUDIBLE]..

01:00:38.610 --> 01:00:39.870 align:middle line:90%
What group to they belong to?

01:00:39.870 --> 01:00:44.400 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Well, they're just
general, nonsingular matrices.

01:00:44.400 --> 01:00:45.890 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:00:45.890 --> 01:00:49.295 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, just 4-by-4
nonsingular matrices.

01:00:49.295 --> 01:00:53.480 align:middle line:90%


01:00:53.480 --> 01:00:57.225 align:middle line:84%
They often can be
chosen to be unitary.

01:00:57.225 --> 01:00:58.600 align:middle line:84%
But, in principle,
you don't have

01:00:58.600 --> 01:01:00.324 align:middle line:90%
to choose them to be unitary.

01:01:00.324 --> 01:01:05.100 align:middle line:90%


01:01:05.100 --> 01:01:08.790 align:middle line:90%
OK, so, now, let's double check.

01:01:08.790 --> 01:01:12.450 align:middle line:84%
So let's call this
equation star star.

01:01:12.450 --> 01:01:17.550 align:middle line:90%
So let's check that star star--

01:01:17.550 --> 01:01:21.030 align:middle line:84%
so we show that, here,
in this representation,

01:01:21.030 --> 01:01:23.520 align:middle line:84%
this is compatible with
Lorentz transformation, OK?

01:01:23.520 --> 01:01:27.750 align:middle line:84%
So we still need
to check star, star

01:01:27.750 --> 01:01:36.150 align:middle line:84%
is compatible with
Lorentz transformation.

01:01:36.150 --> 01:01:41.340 align:middle line:90%


01:01:41.340 --> 01:01:45.720 align:middle line:84%
So what do we mean by this
is compatible with Lorentz

01:01:45.720 --> 01:01:47.740 align:middle line:90%
transformation?

01:01:47.740 --> 01:01:51.220 align:middle line:84%
We mean that, if
we take a psi which

01:01:51.220 --> 01:01:52.630 align:middle line:90%
satisfies this condition--

01:01:52.630 --> 01:01:58.860 align:middle line:90%


01:01:58.860 --> 01:02:04.070 align:middle line:84%
take a psi which
satisfies star star,

01:02:04.070 --> 01:02:06.560 align:middle line:84%
and then we make a
Lorentz transformation psi

01:02:06.560 --> 01:02:15.860 align:middle line:84%
prime equal to S lambda psi,
and then psi prime should also

01:02:15.860 --> 01:02:17.614 align:middle line:90%
satisfy that condition--

01:02:17.614 --> 01:02:21.570 align:middle line:90%


01:02:21.570 --> 01:02:22.440 align:middle line:90%
star star, OK?

01:02:22.440 --> 01:02:24.982 align:middle line:84%
So that means this is compatible
with Lorentz transformation.

01:02:24.982 --> 01:02:29.070 align:middle line:84%
It means that the
psi prime star should

01:02:29.070 --> 01:02:34.740 align:middle line:84%
be equal to the same
as B psi prime, OK?

01:02:34.740 --> 01:02:42.080 align:middle line:84%
So it means that psi prime star
should satisfy that equation.

01:02:42.080 --> 01:02:43.910 align:middle line:90%
So, now, let's check that.

01:02:43.910 --> 01:02:44.870 align:middle line:90%
Now, let's check this.

01:02:44.870 --> 01:02:49.110 align:middle line:90%


01:02:49.110 --> 01:02:53.283 align:middle line:84%
So from here-- so
before checking that,

01:02:53.283 --> 01:02:54.700 align:middle line:84%
do you have any
questions on this?

01:02:54.700 --> 01:02:58.750 align:middle line:90%


01:02:58.750 --> 01:02:59.250 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:59.250 --> 01:03:30.450 align:middle line:90%


01:03:30.450 --> 01:03:33.080 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:03:33.080 --> 01:03:34.850 align:middle line:84%
So, first, from this
equation-- let's

01:03:34.850 --> 01:03:36.095 align:middle line:90%
call this star, star, star.

01:03:36.095 --> 01:03:39.740 align:middle line:90%


01:03:39.740 --> 01:03:42.830 align:middle line:84%
From this star cube
equation, so we

01:03:42.830 --> 01:03:56.780 align:middle line:84%
can find the B when you
act on sigma mu B minus 1.

01:03:56.780 --> 01:04:01.790 align:middle line:84%
So that gives you minus
sigma mu, nu, star, OK?

01:04:01.790 --> 01:04:08.030 align:middle line:84%
So this is obvious because
sigma mu, nu has i there.

01:04:08.030 --> 01:04:10.010 align:middle line:84%
So the minus sign
comes from the i.

01:04:10.010 --> 01:04:15.320 align:middle line:84%
And, otherwise, the B takes each
gamma matrices there into star,

01:04:15.320 --> 01:04:18.080 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:04:18.080 --> 01:04:24.660 align:middle line:84%
And then that means
that the S star, lambda,

01:04:24.660 --> 01:04:30.635 align:middle line:84%
which is given by exponential
1/2 omega mu, nu, sigma star--

01:04:30.635 --> 01:04:33.930 align:middle line:90%


01:04:33.930 --> 01:04:38.675 align:middle line:84%
sigma mu, nu star,
now this is equal to--

01:04:38.675 --> 01:04:45.310 align:middle line:90%


01:04:45.310 --> 01:04:47.815 align:middle line:90%
yeah, you can just plug this in.

01:04:47.815 --> 01:04:50.910 align:middle line:90%


01:04:50.910 --> 01:04:53.620 align:middle line:84%
It just becomes
exponential minus i

01:04:53.620 --> 01:05:06.480 align:middle line:84%
omega mu, nu, B
sigma B minus 1, OK?

01:05:06.480 --> 01:05:07.850 align:middle line:90%
So let me just--

01:05:07.850 --> 01:05:11.850 align:middle line:84%
yeah-- B sigma mu,
nu, B minus 1, OK?

01:05:11.850 --> 01:05:14.640 align:middle line:84%
So I just inserted the
sigma mu, nu, star.

01:05:14.640 --> 01:05:16.440 align:middle line:84%
It's equal to minus
that here, OK?

01:05:16.440 --> 01:05:19.740 align:middle line:90%


01:05:19.740 --> 01:05:23.670 align:middle line:84%
So, now, you can see that this
B minus 1 is in the exponential.

01:05:23.670 --> 01:05:25.980 align:middle line:84%
You can immediately
take it down.

01:05:25.980 --> 01:05:33.295 align:middle line:84%
So that is just equal to
B S lambda B minus 1, OK?

01:05:33.295 --> 01:05:36.970 align:middle line:90%


01:05:36.970 --> 01:05:39.750 align:middle line:84%
So because when you expand
this in power series, B and B

01:05:39.750 --> 01:05:43.710 align:middle line:84%
minus 1 always cancel, except
the first one and the last one.

01:05:43.710 --> 01:05:46.830 align:middle line:84%
So we have used this
trick many times.

01:05:46.830 --> 01:05:52.380 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, and then so we get
a very nice relation that,

01:05:52.380 --> 01:05:56.220 align:middle line:84%
under Lorentz transformation--
so the Lorentz transformation

01:05:56.220 --> 01:05:58.230 align:middle line:84%
matrix on the
complex conjugation,

01:05:58.230 --> 01:06:03.660 align:middle line:84%
again, is generated by this
B, related by this B matrix.

01:06:03.660 --> 01:06:05.415 align:middle line:84%
And, now, it's
just immediate, OK?

01:06:05.415 --> 01:06:09.360 align:middle line:90%


01:06:09.360 --> 01:06:15.080 align:middle line:84%
And now just immediate, so when
you have the psi prime equal

01:06:15.080 --> 01:06:20.560 align:middle line:84%
to that, let's just take the
star of this equation, OK?

01:06:20.560 --> 01:06:36.770 align:middle line:84%
So psi prime star just equal
to S star, lambda psi star, OK?

01:06:36.770 --> 01:06:44.300 align:middle line:84%
So that is equal to B S
lambda B minus 1 and B S--

01:06:44.300 --> 01:06:48.590 align:middle line:90%
B psi, OK?

01:06:48.590 --> 01:06:54.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is equal to
B S lambda psi, OK?

01:06:54.650 --> 01:06:58.190 align:middle line:84%
So this is equal
to B psi prime--

01:06:58.190 --> 01:06:59.780 align:middle line:84%
precisely what we
were trying to show.

01:06:59.780 --> 01:07:09.420 align:middle line:90%


01:07:09.420 --> 01:07:09.920 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:07:09.920 --> 01:07:10.930 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

01:07:10.930 --> 01:07:17.110 align:middle line:90%


01:07:17.110 --> 01:07:19.710 align:middle line:84%
OK, so, now, let me give
you an explicit example

01:07:19.710 --> 01:07:28.320 align:middle line:90%
of this matrix B in the--

01:07:28.320 --> 01:07:30.480 align:middle line:84%
so for this Majorana
representation,

01:07:30.480 --> 01:07:32.760 align:middle line:84%
the B is just equal
to identity, OK?

01:07:32.760 --> 01:07:37.170 align:middle line:84%
So B is just equal to identity
in this representation.

01:07:37.170 --> 01:07:39.772 align:middle line:84%
And, now, let's try to give
you an example of the B

01:07:39.772 --> 01:07:42.330 align:middle line:90%
in the other representation.

01:07:42.330 --> 01:07:46.240 align:middle line:84%
So suppose, in the
chiral representation,

01:07:46.240 --> 01:07:50.160 align:middle line:90%
which I wrote down before--

01:07:50.160 --> 01:07:54.630 align:middle line:84%
so, yeah, I should
not have erased it.

01:07:54.630 --> 01:07:56.220 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, anyway.

01:07:56.220 --> 01:07:59.320 align:middle line:84%
So in the chiral representation
I wrote down before,

01:07:59.320 --> 01:08:01.350 align:middle line:84%
so if you stare at
that expression,

01:08:01.350 --> 01:08:07.185 align:middle line:84%
you find that gamma 0,
gamma 1, and gamma 2--

01:08:07.185 --> 01:08:12.330 align:middle line:84%
or gamma 0, gamma 1, and gamma
3 are imaginary, pure imaginary.

01:08:12.330 --> 01:08:17.880 align:middle line:90%


01:08:17.880 --> 01:08:20.040 align:middle line:90%
And the gamma 2 is real.

01:08:20.040 --> 01:08:22.800 align:middle line:90%


01:08:22.800 --> 01:08:27.720 align:middle line:90%
Gamma 2 is real, OK?

01:08:27.720 --> 01:08:32.370 align:middle line:84%
So this pure imaginary means,
when you take the star of them,

01:08:32.370 --> 01:08:34.210 align:middle line:90%
you get the minus sign.

01:08:34.210 --> 01:08:35.850 align:middle line:84%
So this one, you take
the star of them,

01:08:35.850 --> 01:08:40.160 align:middle line:90%
you just get back to itself.

01:08:40.160 --> 01:08:48.790 align:middle line:84%
So, now, if we look
at this equation,

01:08:48.790 --> 01:08:52.840 align:middle line:84%
so if this is pure
imaginary, you get the star.

01:08:52.840 --> 01:08:55.290 align:middle line:90%
You get the minus itself.

01:08:55.290 --> 01:08:57.420 align:middle line:84%
And then, essentially,
you get the minus self

01:08:57.420 --> 01:09:02.680 align:middle line:84%
means the B actually
anticommutes with gamma mu, OK?

01:09:02.680 --> 01:09:05.590 align:middle line:84%
Because you can just bring
B minus 1 to this side,

01:09:05.590 --> 01:09:10.600 align:middle line:84%
so it just becomes gamma mu
star B equal to B gamma mu.

01:09:10.600 --> 01:09:12.340 align:middle line:84%
So if this is minus
gamma mu, that

01:09:12.340 --> 01:09:16.270 align:middle line:84%
means B should anticommute
with gamma mu, OK?

01:09:16.270 --> 01:09:22.109 align:middle line:84%
But if gamma is real, that means
B will commute with mu, OK?

01:09:22.109 --> 01:09:25.560 align:middle line:84%
If mu is real, then that means
B should commute with mu.

01:09:25.560 --> 01:09:30.990 align:middle line:84%
So, now, in this chiral basis,
these three are pure imaginary.

01:09:30.990 --> 01:09:34.580 align:middle line:84%
That means B needs to
anticommute with them.

01:09:34.580 --> 01:09:35.399 align:middle line:90%
But this is real.

01:09:35.399 --> 01:09:37.770 align:middle line:84%
It means B needs to
commute with this guy.

01:09:37.770 --> 01:09:39.410 align:middle line:90%
Then what is B?

01:09:39.410 --> 01:09:40.400 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Gamma 2.

01:09:40.400 --> 01:09:41.346 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Hmm?

01:09:41.346 --> 01:09:42.240 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Gamma 2.

01:09:42.240 --> 01:09:43.050 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Exactly.

01:09:43.050 --> 01:09:47.005 align:middle line:84%
So B, in this case, can
only be gamma 2, OK?

01:09:47.005 --> 01:09:50.380 align:middle line:90%


01:09:50.380 --> 01:09:53.260 align:middle line:84%
And then we can work
out, what is the Majorana

01:09:53.260 --> 01:09:54.384 align:middle line:90%
condition in this basis--

01:09:54.384 --> 01:09:59.600 align:middle line:90%


01:09:59.600 --> 01:10:01.280 align:middle line:90%
so, essentially, this condition.

01:10:01.280 --> 01:10:04.710 align:middle line:90%


01:10:04.710 --> 01:10:15.890 align:middle line:84%
So that means that the psi star
should be equal to gamma 2 psi,

01:10:15.890 --> 01:10:16.910 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:10:16.910 --> 01:10:20.040 align:middle line:84%
So that's the Majorana
condition here.

01:10:20.040 --> 01:10:22.400 align:middle line:84%
So, now, remember,
in the chiral basis,

01:10:22.400 --> 01:10:26.870 align:middle line:84%
we can write psi in terms
of the psi L and psi R.

01:10:26.870 --> 01:10:28.910 align:middle line:84%
So, essentially, we
have this condition.

01:10:28.910 --> 01:10:35.860 align:middle line:90%


01:10:35.860 --> 01:10:38.210 align:middle line:90%
So I erased my gamma 2.

01:10:38.210 --> 01:10:40.160 align:middle line:90%
So I saw the gamma 2--

01:10:40.160 --> 01:10:42.290 align:middle line:90%
let me write it here explicitly.

01:10:42.290 --> 01:10:54.670 align:middle line:84%
It's minus i gamma 2, 0 minus i
sigma 2 and sigma 2, here, OK?

01:10:54.670 --> 01:10:56.440 align:middle line:84%
So, now, if you look
at this condition,

01:10:56.440 --> 01:11:00.460 align:middle line:84%
this means that no longer
psi L and psi R are no longer

01:11:00.460 --> 01:11:02.060 align:middle line:90%
independent of each other.

01:11:02.060 --> 01:11:08.680 align:middle line:84%
So psi L star should be equal
to minus i sigma 2 psi R

01:11:08.680 --> 01:11:14.280 align:middle line:84%
or, equivalently, psi R
equal to i sigma 2 psi L--

01:11:14.280 --> 01:11:17.340 align:middle line:90%


01:11:17.340 --> 01:11:20.550 align:middle line:90%
or L star, OK?

01:11:20.550 --> 01:11:25.340 align:middle line:84%
So, in this case, the psi,
then, have the following form--

01:11:25.340 --> 01:11:30.450 align:middle line:84%
psi L i sigma 2
psi L. So sigma R

01:11:30.450 --> 01:11:35.010 align:middle line:84%
just can be expressed
in terms of sigma L.

01:11:35.010 --> 01:11:41.160 align:middle line:84%
So this is the Majorana spinor
in the chiral basis, OK?

01:11:41.160 --> 01:11:44.550 align:middle line:84%
You see, there are only four
independent, real components

01:11:44.550 --> 01:11:48.270 align:middle line:84%
because each psi L is two
complex components, OK?

01:11:48.270 --> 01:11:51.950 align:middle line:90%


01:11:51.950 --> 01:11:52.580 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:11:52.580 --> 01:11:54.038 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So why
do you [INAUDIBLE]

01:11:54.038 --> 01:11:58.023 align:middle line:84%
that psi and psi star are
not independent [INAUDIBLE]??

01:11:58.023 --> 01:11:58.606 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Hmm?

01:11:58.606 --> 01:11:59.380 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Why are they--

01:11:59.380 --> 01:12:00.255 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No, no, no.

01:12:00.255 --> 01:12:03.360 align:middle line:84%
No, here, we are imposing
this condition, right?

01:12:03.360 --> 01:12:05.610 align:middle line:90%
We are imposing this condition.

01:12:05.610 --> 01:12:06.110 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:12:06.110 --> 01:12:07.568 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, this is
Majorana condition we

01:12:07.568 --> 01:12:09.040 align:middle line:90%
want to impose in this basis.

01:12:09.040 --> 01:12:12.005 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: And this is now
independent of massless

01:12:12.005 --> 01:12:12.880 align:middle line:90%
or massive particles?

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:14.030 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:12:14.030 --> 01:12:15.260 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, this is-- yeah.

01:12:15.260 --> 01:12:18.730 align:middle line:90%


01:12:18.730 --> 01:12:20.140 align:middle line:90%
Good?

01:12:20.140 --> 01:12:24.100 align:middle line:84%
So this concludes our discussion
of the Majorana spinor.

01:12:24.100 --> 01:12:26.670 align:middle line:84%
Do you have any
questions on this?

01:12:26.670 --> 01:12:27.390 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:12:27.390 --> 01:12:33.200 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So is the
orthogonal component of psi--

01:12:33.200 --> 01:12:36.240 align:middle line:84%
the Majorana
fermion [INAUDIBLE]??

01:12:36.240 --> 01:12:37.020 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Sorry?

01:12:37.020 --> 01:12:38.437 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The
orthogonal component

01:12:38.437 --> 01:12:41.800 align:middle line:90%
of this Majorana species--

01:12:41.800 --> 01:12:44.740 align:middle line:84%
like, possible--
in the chiral one,

01:12:44.740 --> 01:12:47.060 align:middle line:84%
like, psi L, and
then you [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:47.060 --> 01:12:50.265 align:middle line:84%
and then psi R. [INAUDIBLE]
two components of psi.

01:12:50.265 --> 01:12:50.890 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

01:12:50.890 --> 01:12:52.180 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: So we are--

01:12:52.180 --> 01:12:54.910 align:middle line:84%
we have one component
of psi, and there

01:12:54.910 --> 01:12:57.080 align:middle line:90%
should be another one, right?

01:12:57.080 --> 01:12:57.705 align:middle line:90%
So is that one?

01:12:57.705 --> 01:12:58.372 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Sorry.

01:12:58.372 --> 01:13:00.440 align:middle line:84%
I don't quite understand
your question.

01:13:00.440 --> 01:13:01.607 align:middle line:90%
Say it again-- what?

01:13:01.607 --> 01:13:02.690 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK, [INAUDIBLE].

01:13:02.690 --> 01:13:03.950 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: OK, OK.

01:13:03.950 --> 01:13:04.670 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

01:13:04.670 --> 01:13:05.270 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:13:05.270 --> 01:13:07.580 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So, I guess, related
to an earlier question,

01:13:07.580 --> 01:13:09.470 align:middle line:84%
how do we consider
handedness here

01:13:09.470 --> 01:13:13.792 align:middle line:84%
for a massless particle that's
also the Majorana, which psi L

01:13:13.792 --> 01:13:17.070 align:middle line:90%
and psi R are [INAUDIBLE]?

01:13:17.070 --> 01:13:18.150 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Right.

01:13:18.150 --> 01:13:24.982 align:middle line:90%
So for the-- yeah, if we--

01:13:24.982 --> 01:13:26.440 align:middle line:84%
for massless
particle, you can just

01:13:26.440 --> 01:13:30.850 align:middle line:84%
direct it because then you don't
have to think about the psi R,

01:13:30.850 --> 01:13:34.510 align:middle line:84%
and this, you just have the
same number degrees of freedom

01:13:34.510 --> 01:13:35.620 align:middle line:90%
as a massless particle.

01:13:35.620 --> 01:13:40.330 align:middle line:90%


01:13:40.330 --> 01:13:42.160 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

01:13:42.160 --> 01:13:42.660 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:13:42.660 --> 01:13:45.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:45.500 --> 01:13:46.320 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

01:13:46.320 --> 01:13:49.220 align:middle line:84%
So let's now go
to the next topic.

01:13:49.220 --> 01:13:52.160 align:middle line:84%
We only have a few minutes,
so we can only just

01:13:52.160 --> 01:13:53.285 align:middle line:90%
make some general comments.

01:13:53.285 --> 01:14:01.260 align:middle line:90%


01:14:01.260 --> 01:14:03.450 align:middle line:84%
So so far, mostly,
we have been talking

01:14:03.450 --> 01:14:05.430 align:middle line:90%
about continuous symmetries.

01:14:05.430 --> 01:14:09.060 align:middle line:90%


01:14:09.060 --> 01:14:14.635 align:middle line:84%
But there are also
discrete symmetries, OK?

01:14:14.635 --> 01:14:17.960 align:middle line:90%


01:14:17.960 --> 01:14:25.930 align:middle line:84%
So, by definition,
discrete symmetries

01:14:25.930 --> 01:14:33.505 align:middle line:84%
are symmetries, which don't
have continuous parameters, OK?

01:14:33.505 --> 01:14:37.780 align:middle line:90%


01:14:37.780 --> 01:14:40.300 align:middle line:84%
So continuous symmetries
are symmetries, which--

01:14:40.300 --> 01:14:43.450 align:middle line:90%


01:14:43.450 --> 01:14:46.390 align:middle line:84%
yeah, which the
transformation dependence

01:14:46.390 --> 01:14:48.520 align:middle line:90%
on continuous parameter.

01:14:48.520 --> 01:14:50.770 align:middle line:84%
Discrete symmetries,
you just don't, OK?

01:14:50.770 --> 01:14:53.740 align:middle line:84%
You don't have
continuous parameter.

01:14:53.740 --> 01:14:58.690 align:middle line:84%
So simple example-- say,
let's imagine we have--

01:14:58.690 --> 01:15:01.555 align:middle line:84%
so this real scalar theory--
we can see that before.

01:15:01.555 --> 01:15:11.410 align:middle line:90%


01:15:11.410 --> 01:15:15.150 align:middle line:84%
So this theory has a discrete
symmetry because this

01:15:15.150 --> 01:15:16.950 align:middle line:90%
is invariant under phi.

01:15:16.950 --> 01:15:20.940 align:middle line:90%
It goes to minus phi, OK?

01:15:20.940 --> 01:15:23.790 align:middle line:84%
So because you see all
the terms are even,

01:15:23.790 --> 01:15:27.150 align:middle line:84%
so it's invariant under
phi go to minus phi.

01:15:27.150 --> 01:15:29.880 align:middle line:84%
And this transformation is
no continuous parameter, OK?

01:15:29.880 --> 01:15:33.190 align:middle line:90%
So this is a discrete symmetry.

01:15:33.190 --> 01:15:35.940 align:middle line:90%
And so this is--

01:15:35.940 --> 01:15:37.873 align:middle line:84%
if you do it twice,
you go back to itself.

01:15:37.873 --> 01:15:39.540 align:middle line:84%
So this is often
called the Z2 symmetry.

01:15:39.540 --> 01:15:43.500 align:middle line:90%


01:15:43.500 --> 01:15:45.330 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is called
the Z2 symmetry.

01:15:45.330 --> 01:15:48.480 align:middle line:90%


01:15:48.480 --> 01:15:53.540 align:middle line:84%
And there are also spacetime
discrete symmetries, OK?

01:15:53.540 --> 01:15:55.940 align:middle line:84%
So this is an internal discrete
symmetry-- have nothing

01:15:55.940 --> 01:15:57.740 align:middle line:90%
to do with spacetime, OK?

01:15:57.740 --> 01:16:00.170 align:middle line:84%
There are also spacetime
discrete symmetries.

01:16:00.170 --> 01:16:14.640 align:middle line:90%


01:16:14.640 --> 01:16:18.350 align:middle line:84%
So spacetime discrete symmetries
including, say, if we consider

01:16:18.350 --> 01:16:19.850 align:middle line:90%
Minkowski spacetime--

01:16:19.850 --> 01:16:27.610 align:middle line:90%


01:16:27.610 --> 01:16:30.820 align:middle line:84%
so you can have t
goes to minus t.

01:16:30.820 --> 01:16:38.300 align:middle line:84%
So you can have
so-called time reversal,

01:16:38.300 --> 01:16:44.110 align:middle line:84%
which corresponding to your
t, x goes to minus t, x, OK?

01:16:44.110 --> 01:16:47.050 align:middle line:90%
You just transform the time.

01:16:47.050 --> 01:16:49.095 align:middle line:84%
You can also have
the so-called parity.

01:16:49.095 --> 01:16:52.500 align:middle line:90%


01:16:52.500 --> 01:16:53.640 align:middle line:90%
You take t.

01:16:53.640 --> 01:17:00.315 align:middle line:84%
Then you revert all the
spatial direction, OK?

01:17:00.315 --> 01:17:09.000 align:middle line:90%


01:17:09.000 --> 01:17:13.110 align:middle line:84%
So comment that you
can ask why we actually

01:17:13.110 --> 01:17:16.230 align:middle line:90%
reverse all three directions.

01:17:16.230 --> 01:17:18.690 align:middle line:84%
How about if I just
reverse one direction

01:17:18.690 --> 01:17:21.060 align:middle line:90%
or reverse two directions, OK?

01:17:21.060 --> 01:17:23.910 align:middle line:84%
That seems also to be
a discrete symmetry.

01:17:23.910 --> 01:17:25.270 align:middle line:90%
And indeed.

01:17:25.270 --> 01:17:28.310 align:middle line:84%
So if you just change
the directions,

01:17:28.310 --> 01:17:32.220 align:middle line:84%
say, in the x direction, that's
also a discrete symmetry.

01:17:32.220 --> 01:17:33.940 align:middle line:84%
And if you only
change the direction

01:17:33.940 --> 01:17:35.640 align:middle line:84%
in both x and the
y direction, that's

01:17:35.640 --> 01:17:37.690 align:middle line:90%
also a discrete symmetry.

01:17:37.690 --> 01:17:42.510 align:middle line:90%
But if you change--

01:17:42.510 --> 01:17:46.870 align:middle line:84%
if you do the reflection
in two directions,

01:17:46.870 --> 01:17:49.840 align:middle line:84%
that's equivalent to
a 90-degree rotation--

01:17:49.840 --> 01:17:57.670 align:middle line:84%
a 180-degree rotation
in that plane, OK?

01:17:57.670 --> 01:18:02.270 align:middle line:84%
And so it's part of the
continuous symmetries,

01:18:02.270 --> 01:18:06.200 align:middle line:84%
so it's not independent
discrete symmetry.

01:18:06.200 --> 01:18:10.430 align:middle line:84%
And now, when you change all
three directions compared

01:18:10.430 --> 01:18:13.580 align:middle line:84%
to change one direction,
you differ only

01:18:13.580 --> 01:18:15.390 align:middle line:90%
by changing two directions.

01:18:15.390 --> 01:18:17.240 align:middle line:84%
So that means changing
all three directions

01:18:17.240 --> 01:18:18.907 align:middle line:84%
and changing one
direction-- they differ

01:18:18.907 --> 01:18:21.380 align:middle line:90%
by 180-degree rotation, OK?

01:18:21.380 --> 01:18:23.060 align:middle line:84%
So that means that
when you change--

01:18:23.060 --> 01:18:29.040 align:middle line:84%
this is the only independent
discrete symmetry

01:18:29.040 --> 01:18:33.150 align:middle line:84%
from the spatial
reflection point of view.

01:18:33.150 --> 01:18:35.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:18:35.160 --> 01:18:40.030 align:middle line:90%
So for a complex scalar field--

01:18:40.030 --> 01:18:42.060 align:middle line:84%
so if you consider
complex scalar field--

01:18:42.060 --> 01:18:48.630 align:middle line:90%


01:18:48.630 --> 01:18:52.320 align:middle line:84%
if you can see the
complex scalar field,

01:18:52.320 --> 01:18:57.380 align:middle line:84%
then this is no longer
a discrete symmetry

01:18:57.380 --> 01:19:01.220 align:middle line:84%
because, remember, we can
rotate phi by a phase.

01:19:01.220 --> 01:19:02.900 align:middle line:84%
When you rotate
the phi by a phase,

01:19:02.900 --> 01:19:04.970 align:middle line:84%
if you take that
phase to be pi--

01:19:04.970 --> 01:19:08.630 align:middle line:84%
say, exponential i pi-- and
then you take to be minus phi.

01:19:08.630 --> 01:19:11.000 align:middle line:84%
And so, in that
case, this is part

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:12.890 align:middle line:84%
of the continuous
symmetry, so it's no longer

01:19:12.890 --> 01:19:15.500 align:middle line:90%
independent discrete symmetry.

01:19:15.500 --> 01:19:17.090 align:middle line:84%
But, here, there's,
nevertheless,

01:19:17.090 --> 01:19:19.910 align:middle line:90%
another discrete symmetry.

01:19:19.910 --> 01:19:22.400 align:middle line:84%
Can you see what is the other
independent discrete symmetry

01:19:22.400 --> 01:19:23.880 align:middle line:90%
here?

01:19:23.880 --> 01:19:25.690 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:19:25.690 --> 01:19:26.230 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:19:26.230 --> 01:19:30.430 align:middle line:84%
You can take phi
to phi star, OK?

01:19:30.430 --> 01:19:33.640 align:middle line:84%
You can exchange
phi to phi star, OK?

01:19:33.640 --> 01:19:35.020 align:middle line:90%
It's a complex conjugation.

01:19:35.020 --> 01:19:38.460 align:middle line:84%
And this is often called
charge conjugation.

01:19:38.460 --> 01:19:44.360 align:middle line:90%


01:19:44.360 --> 01:19:44.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:19:44.860 --> 01:19:48.460 align:middle line:84%
This is often called charge
conjugation because, remember,

01:19:48.460 --> 01:19:53.270 align:middle line:84%
heuristically, we can
think of phi as create--

01:19:53.270 --> 01:19:55.270 align:middle line:84%
yeah, it's just one of
them create the particle,

01:19:55.270 --> 01:19:57.350 align:middle line:84%
and the other create
the antiparticle.

01:19:57.350 --> 01:19:59.770 align:middle line:84%
And they have
opposite charge, OK?

01:19:59.770 --> 01:20:01.900 align:middle line:84%
So it's called a
charge conjugation.

01:20:01.900 --> 01:20:05.470 align:middle line:84%
So, this, will give
a symbol called T--

01:20:05.470 --> 01:20:09.610 align:middle line:84%
script T. And, this, we give
a symbol called P-- script P.

01:20:09.610 --> 01:20:13.300 align:middle line:84%
And, this, we give a
symbol called script C. So,

01:20:13.300 --> 01:20:16.420 align:middle line:84%
altogether, they are
called CPT symmetry, OK?

01:20:16.420 --> 01:20:16.920 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:20:16.920 --> 01:20:19.140 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let's stop here.

01:20:19.140 --> 01:20:23.000 align:middle line:90%